://www.news18.com/news/india/karnataka-seals-its-borders-announces-free-ration-for-all-for-2-months-as-covid-19-cases-reach-20-2546273.html|website=News18|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> [[Andhra Pradesh]] CM [[Y. S. Jaganmohan Reddy]] announced free ration for the poor.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/ap-announces-lockdown-till-march-31/1776396|title=AP announces lockdown till March 31|date=|work=Outlook India|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Telangana]] CM announced that white [[Ration card (India)|ration card]] holders will be provided with 12 kilograms of free rice per person (against a monthly supply of 6 kilograms per card person) through [[ration shop]]s. On 23 March, [[Bihar]] [[Chief minister (India)|CM]] [[Nitish Kumar]] announced one month of free ration for all ration card holders.\n\nOn 25 March, Union Minister [[Prakash Javadekar]] announced that 80[[Crore|{{Nbsp}}crore]] (800[[Crore|{{Nbsp}}]]<nowiki/>million) people would be given wheat at the rate of Rs 2 per kg, and rice at Rs 3 per kg. He also said that three months ration advance would be given.<ref>{{cite web |title=Cabinet Meet Live Updates: Centre To Provide 7 Kg Ration To 80 Crore| url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/economy-finance/cabinet-meet-live-updates-government-to-announce-decisions-taken-amid-coronavirus-outbreak-nirmala-sitharaman-narendra-modi-labour-minister-workforce-financial-plan-measures-direct-benefit-transfer-gdp-economy|website=bloombergquint|author=}}</ref>\n\n===Masks and supplies===\nOn 25 March, [[Vivo (technology company)|Vivo]] said that they would be donating 1 lakh [[Medical mask|surgical]] and 5,000 [[NIOSH air filtration rating|N95 masks]] to [[Maharashtra]] government.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/industry/technology/coronavirus-outbreak-vivo-to-donate-1-lakh-protective-masks-to-maharashtra-govt-xiaomi-suspends-local-manufacturing/1909019/|title=Coronavirus outbreak: Vivo to donate 1 lakh protective masks to Maharashtra Govt, Xiaomi suspends local manufacturing|date=|work=Financial Express|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> On 26 March, former Indian [[cricketers]], [[Irfan Pathan]] and [[Yusuf Pathan]], made a donation of 4,000 masks.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/coronavirus-outbreak-former-india-cricketers-irfan-pathan-yusuf-pathan-donate-4000-masks-amidst-rising-covid-19-cases-8180911.html|title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Former India cricketers Irfan Pathan, Yusuf Pathan donate 4,000 masks amidst rising COVID-19 cases|date=|work=Firstpost|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, [[Hyundai Motor India Limited|Hyundai India]] announced placing an order for 25,000 COVID-19 Advanced Diagnostic Testing Kits from [[South Korea]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://auto.ndtv.com/news/coronavirus-lockdown-hyundai-orders-advanced-covid-19-testing-kits-for-india-2202063|title=Coronavirus Lockdown: Hyundai India Orders Advanced COVID-19 Testing Kits From Korea|last=|first=|date=|website=CarandBike|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIndia hasn't experienced [[Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 related shortages]] so far.\n\n{{As of|2020|April|3}}, [[Indian Railways]] had produced total of 2[[Lakh|{{Nbsp}}lakh]] (200,000) masks and 25,000 sanitisers.<ref>{{cite web |title=Railway workers produce sanitisers & masks| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/hyderabad/rly-workers-produce-sanitisers-masks/articleshow/74957651.cms|website=timesofindia|author=| date= 3 April 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date= 3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Situation==\n===Panic buying===\n{{See also|Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nHyderabad witnessed panic buying throughout 20th evening and Saturday 21st.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nanisetti |first1=Serish |title=Panicky shoppers clear out grocery shops |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/panicked-shoppers-clear-out-grocery-shops/article31131827.ece |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=22 March 2020}}</ref> Panic buying of milk and other dairy products was also reported.<ref>{{cite news |title=No need for panic buying of milk |url=https://ahmedabadmirror.indiatimes.com/ahmedabad/others/no-need-for-panic-buying-of-milk/articleshow/74754049.cms |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Ahmedabad Mirror |date=22 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=No need for panic buying of milk, other dairy products, says Amul MD |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/no-need-for-panic-buying-of-milk-other-dairy-products-says-amul-md/articleshow/74750809.cms |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Economic Times |agency=PTI |date=21 March 2020}}</ref> Online grocery delivery service [[Grofers]] also witnessed panic buying across states.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haq |first1=Haq |last2=Chitlangia |first2=Risha |title=Coronavirus: Govt monitors supplies to ease panic buying crunch |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/coronavirus-govt-monitors-supplies-to-ease-panic-buying-crunch/story-GKXs9RkVgkkyfcRv1ZNFuN.html |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nRetailers and consumer goods firms saw their average daily sales more than double on 19 March as consumers rushed to buy essentials ahead of [[Prime minister|PM]] [[Narendra Modi|Modi]]\u2019s address to the nation.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/panic-buying-goes-a-notch-up-ahead-of-pm-modis-address/articleshow/74721852.cms|title=Panic buying goes a notch up ahead of PM Modi's address|date=|work=Economic Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> In response to this, Modi assured the citizens that there was enough food and ration supplies and advised them against panic buying.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/india/coronavirus-outbreak-pm-modis-9-key-messages-for-indians/articleshow/74716261.cms|title=Janata curfew, avoid panic buying, stay at home: PM Modi's 9 key messages for Indians|date=|work=Times of India|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Escaping of suspected people ===\nSeveral cases are reported across the country, where people who are suspected to have come in contact with the virus, escaped from the quarantines and hospitals.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/11-coronavirus-suspects-in-navi-mumbai-traced-readmitted20200316214213/|title=11 coronavirus suspects in Navi Mumbai traced, readmitted|website=ANI News|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/5-coronavirus-suspects-escape-from-isolation-ward-of-nagpur-hospital-all-traced/story-WqxUDicK8Ejeczq1yatULM.html|title=5 coronavirus suspects escape from isolation ward of Nagpur hospital, all traced|date=14 March 2020|website=Hindustan Times|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Chhattisgarh]], a 35 yr-old man from Tagapani, Dhamtari, who was put under isolation home by the health dept after his return from [[Tamil Nadu]], committed suicide.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chhattisgarh: Covid-19 suspect under home quarantine commits suicide in Dhamtari| url=https://m.timesofindia.com/city/raipur/chhattisgarh-covid-19-suspect-under-home-quarantine-commits-suicide-in-dhamtari/articleshow/74899263.cms|website=timesofindia|author=| date=31 March 2020|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Gujarat]], 93 people have broken self-isolation rules in 10 days. FIRs have been filed against 10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/ahmedabad/in-gujarat-93-flouted-self-isolation-rules-in-10-days-firs-against-10-6327258/|title=In Gujarat, 93 flouted self-isolation rules in 10 days, FIRs against 10|last=Ghosh|first=Sohini|last2=Jha|first2=Vaibhav|date=23 March 2020|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nTwo expats in Kasaragod district, [[Kerala]], who violated quarantine measures were subjected to punitive measures, including cancellation of their Indian passports.<ref>{{cite news |title=Passports of two NRIs to be cancelled for violating quarantine orders in Kasaragod |url=https://english.mathrubhumi.com/news/kerala/passports-of-two-nris-to-be-cancelled-for-violating-quarantine-orders-in-kasaragod-1.4640844 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Mathrubhumi |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, A case of 26-year-old woman suspected of being infected with the corona virus has been reported to have fled the hospital in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]]. The woman, who hails from Mohali, recently returned from the US and was brought to a government hospital in [[Chandigarh]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus in India: Mohali woman who travelled to UK tests positive| url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-in-india-mohali-woman-who-travelled-to-uk-tests-positive-1657743-2020-03-20|website=indiatoday|author=}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March in [[Telangana]], one woman returned from [[Singapore]] has been missing, while a man who came from [[Doha]] went somewhere without telling hospital staff.<ref>{{cite web |title=Covidiots everywhere; cases of foreign returnees flouting home quarantine in rise| url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/nation/current-affairs/230320/covidiots-everywhere-cases-of-foreign-returnees-flouting-home-quarant.html|website=Deccan chronicle|author=}}</ref>\n\n===Misinformation and discrimination===\n{{see also|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Xenophobia and racism related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nDespite evidence to the contrary, a viral rumour spread online alleging that only people who eat meat were affected by coronavirus, causing \"#NoMeat_NoCoronaVirus\" to trend on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=3 March 2020|title='No Meat, No Coronavirus' Makes No Sense|url=https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|website=The Wire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303034133/https://thewire.in/health/meat-eating-2019-novel-coronavirus-wuhan-bats-proteins-cattle-climate-cow-vigilantism|archive-date=3 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> To curb these rumours and combat declining sales, some poultry industry associations held a \"Chicken and Egg Mela\" in Hyderabad. Several Telangana state ministers were in attendance and ate some of the free eggs and fried chicken being distributed at the event to show their support for the industry.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=3 March 2020|title=Amid COVID-19 fears, KTR relishes chicken and eggs to dispel rumours|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/hyderabad/2020/feb/29/amid-covid-19-fears-ktr-relishes-chicken-and-eggs-to-dispel-rumours-2110056.html|website=The New Indian Express|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303034135/https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/hyderabad/2020/feb/29/amid-covid-19-fears-ktr-relishes-chicken-and-eggs-to-dispel-rumours-2110056.html|archive-date=3 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMuslim cleric Ilyas Sharafuddin has stated that [[Allah]] has punished the Chinese by unleashing Corona virus on them for their brutal crackdown on [[Uyghurs|Uighur]] Muslims. His claim was largely criticised and was condemned for passing such communal and insensitive comments.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/india/article/allah-unleashed-coronavirus-on-chinese-for-persecuting-uighur-muslims-islamic-cleric-ilyas-sharafuddin/546408|title=Allah unleashed Coronavirus on Chinese for persecuting Uighur Muslims: Islamic cleric Ilyas Sharafuddin|website=www.timesnownews.com}}</ref>\n\nSome politicians like [[Swami Chakrapani]] and [[Suman Haripriya]] claimed that drinking cow urine and applying cow dung on the body can cure coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|title=Coronavirus: Can cow dung and urine help cure the novel coronavirus?|website=Times of India|accessdate=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206035509/https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/life-style/health-fitness/health-news/coronavirus-in-india-can-cow-dung-and-urine-help-cure-the-novel-coronavirus/articleshow/73952691.cms|archive-date=6 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|title=Novel coronavirus can be cured with gaumutra, gobar claims Assam BJP MLA Suman Haripriya|website=Firstpost|accessdate=5 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304051130/https://www.firstpost.com/india/novel-coronavirus-can-be-cured-with-gaumutra-gobar-claims-assam-bjp-mla-suman-haripriya-8111021.html|archive-date=4 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> WHO's chief scientist [[Soumya Swaminathan (scientist)|Soumya Swaminathan]] rubbished such claims and criticised these politicians for spreading misinformation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://swachhindia.ndtv.com/novel-coronavirus-outbreak-indias-response-and-surveillance-has-been-quite-robust-says-whos-chief-scientist-42015|title=Novel Coronavirus Outbreak: \"India's Response And Surveillance Has Been Quite Robust,\" Says WHO's Chief Scientist|website=NDTV|date=3 March 2020|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-51910099|title=India's coronavirus health myths fact-checked|first=Reality Check|last=team|date=19 March 2020|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref>\n\nReports of harassment of people from [[Northeast India]], which shares a border with [[Tibet Autonomous Region|Tibet]] and [[Myanmar]], in Chennai, Pune and Hyderabad have been reported following the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |title=Northeast community fends off racist attacks with coronavirus |url=https://punemirror.indiatimes.com/pune/cover-story/northeast-community-fends-off-racist-attacks-with-coronavirus-label/articleshow/74542293.cms |website=pune mirror |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=We are the Coronavirus for few Indians': says people from North-east in Hyderabad |url=https://newsmeter.in/we-are-the-coronavirus-for-few-indians-says-people-from-north-east/ |website=newsmeter |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Covid-19: Northeast India Welfare Association complains of racism |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-northeast-india-welfare-association-complains-of-racial-discrimination-in-chennai/articleshow/74733326.cms |website=timesofindia |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> Students from [[Kirori Mal College]] in Delhi, [[Tata Institute of Social Sciences]] in Mumbai and other institutes in Kolkata have also faced harassment and filed complaints with authorities.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus outbreak: NE students at TISS report incidents of 'racism, harassment' |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/coronavirus-outbreak-northeastern-students-at-tiss-report-incidents-of-racism-harassment-6272973/ |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=The Indian Express |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218172700/https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/coronavirus-outbreak-northeastern-students-at-tiss-report-incidents-of-racism-harassment-6272973/ |archive-date=18 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2 Students Allegedly Faced Racial Taunts Linked To Coronavirus In Kolkata |url=https://www.ndtv.com/kolkata-news/coronavirus-outbreak-2-students-allegedly-faced-racial-taunts-linked-to-coronavirus-in-kolkata-2196428 |website=ndtv |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus outbreak: NE students at TISS report incidents of 'racism, harassment' |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/cities/mumbai/coronavirus-outbreak-northeastern-students-at-tiss-report-incidents-of-racism-harassment-6272973/ |website=Indianexpress |accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMisinformation that the government is spreading \"anti-corona\" drug in the country during Janata curfew went viral on social media.<ref>{{cite news |title=Is government spraying coronavirus vaccine using airplanes? No, it\u2019s fake news |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/it-s-viral/is-government-spraying-coronavirus-vaccine-using-airplanes-no-it-s-fake-news/story-QmSDrfLW8SkSghT2TUf5cK.html |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Hindustan Times |date=20 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Film actor [[Mohanlal]] and many others shared the fake news that, the vibration generated by clapping together during Janata curfew will kill the virus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/mohanlal-many-others-share-fake-info-clapping-may-kill-virus-pib-debunks-120844 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |title=Mohanlal, many others share fake info that \u2018clapping may kill virus\u2019, PIB debunks |work=[[The News Minute]]}}</ref> One viral message says that the lifetime of coronavirus is only 12 hours and staying home for 14 hours during Janata curfew break the chain of transmission.<ref name=indiatoday1>{{cite news |last1=DelhiMarch 21 |first1=Ratna New |last2=March 21 |first2=Ratna New |last3=Ist |first3=Ratna New |title=Fact Check: Social media users give misleading twist to PM Modi's concept of 'Janta curfew' |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/fact-check/story/social-media-users-give-misleading-twist-pm-modi-janta-curfew-1658195-2020-03-21 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref> Another message claimed that observing Janata curfew will result in the reduction of coronavirus cases by 40%.<ref name=indiatoday1/> Tweet by [[Rajinikanth]] claiming that a 14-hour stay home can stop the coronavirus disease going from \"stage 2\" to \"stage 3\" was classified as misinformation and was taken down by Twitter for violating community guidelines.<ref>{{cite news |last1=ChennaiMarch 21 |first1=India Today Web Desk |last2=March 21 |first2=India Today Web Desk |last3=Ist |first3=India Today Web Desk |title=Twitter takes down Rajinikanth's Janata Curfew video for spreading misinformation |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/movies/regional-cinema/story/twitter-takes-down-rajinikanth-s-janata-curfew-video-for-spreading-misinformation-1658282-2020-03-21 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref> [[Amitabh Bachchan]] was heavily criticised for one of his tweets, which claimed vibrations from clapping, blowing conch shells as part of Sunday's Janata Curfew would have reduced or destroyed coronavirus potency as it was \u2018[[amavasya]]\u2019, the darkest day of the month.<ref>{{cite news |title=Amitabh Bachchan deletes post on \u2018clapping vibrations destroy virus potency\u2019 after being called out |url=https://trib.al/Bcqp2dp |work=The Hindu |date=23 March 2020 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\nResidents of a village named ''Korauna'' in [[Sitapur district]] in [[Uttar Pradesh]] faced discrimination due to similarity in name of the village with the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/people-confuse-ups-korauna-for-corona-outsiders-even-wont-take-a-phone-call-from-village20200329195919|title=People confuse UP's Korauna for Corona; outsiders even won't take a phone call from village|work=ANI|date=29 March 2020|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome doctors and medical workers were evicted from their homes over fears they may be carrying coronavirus. In cases reported across the country, healthcare professionals described the growing stigma they are facing from their neighbours and landlords, resulting in many being refused taxis, barricaded from their own homes, or made homeless.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/30/indian-doctors-being-evicted-from-homes-over-coronavirus-fears |title=Indian doctors being evicted from homes over coronavirus fears |work=The Guardian |date=30 March 2020 |authors=Hannah Ellis Petersen |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/bengal-kolkata-landlords-evict-medical-professionals-coronavirus-1659333-2020-03-25 |title=Kolkata landlords evict medical professionals, Resident Doctor's Association steps in |work=India Today |date=25 March 2020 |authors=Romita Datta |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, foreigners from countries such as UK, US and Israel were facing hostility, including evictions from rented homes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/foreign-tourists-face-hostility-india-coronavirus-panic-200324083648362.html|title=Foreign tourists face hostility in India amid coronavirus panic|work=[[Al Jazeera]]|date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n\nThe numbers are from data published by Ministry of Health and Family Welfare on their website.{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India medical cases}} {{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India medical cases summary}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Confirmed Indian cases abroad===\nThe Ministry of External Affairs has confirmed that there are 276 confirmed Indians cases abroad as of 18 March. Most of them were in Iran (255), with others in United Arab Emirates, Italy, Kuwait, Sri Lanka, Rwanda and Hong Kong.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/indians-including-iran-test-positive-for-coronavirus-abroad-confirms-mea-1656927-2020-03-18|title=276 Indians including 255 in Iran test positive for coronavirus abroad, confirms MEA|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> One Indian died in Iran on 20 March 2020.<ref name=\"Iran\">{{Cite news|last=Chaudhury|first=Dipanjan Roy|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-one-indian-in-iran-dead-government-gives-local-help-to-254-others/articleshow/74722021.cms|title=Covid-19: One Indian in Iran dead, Government gives local help to 254 others|date=20 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref> A 3-year-old Indian girl tested positive in Singapore on 26 March, taking total to 277.<ref name=singapore>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/india/article/3-yr-old-indian-girl-among-73-new-coronavirus-cases-in-singapore-tally-of-infected-people-crosses/569723|title=3-yr-old Indian girl among 73 new coronavirus cases in Singapore, tally of infected people crosses 600|website=www.timesnownews.com|agency=PTI|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> In Kuwait, a 46-year-old Indian died on 4 April.<ref name=\"Kuwait\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kuna.net.kw/ArticleDetails.aspx?id=2884135&language=en|title=Kuwait reports 1st coronavirus death, 62 new cases|website=Kuwait News Agency|date=4 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:right; font-size:90%;\"\n|+\nConfirmed cases of Indian nationals abroad\n!Country/Region\n!Active cases\n!Death\n!Total\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Hong Kong}}\n|1\n| style=\"color:gray;\" |0\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Iran}}\n|254\n|1<ref name=\"Iran\"/>\n|255\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Italy}}\n|5\n| style=\"color:gray;\" |0\n|5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Kuwait}}\n| style=\"color:gray;\" |0\n|1<ref name=\"Kuwait\"/>\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Rwanda}}\n|1\n| style=\"color:gray;\" |0\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|United Arab Emirates}}\n|12\n| style=\"color:gray;\" |0\n|12\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Sri Lanka}}\n|1\n| style=\"color:gray;\" |0\n|1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flag|Singapore}}\n|1\n| style=\"color:gray;\" |0\n|1<ref name=singapore/>\n|-\n!Total\n!275\n!2\n!277\n|}\n\n=== States and Union Territories without confirmed cases ===\n\nNo confirmed cases have been reported in the following states and union territories\n* [[Meghalaya]]\n* [[Nagaland]]\n* [[Sikkim]]\n* [[Dadra and Nagar Haveli and Daman and Diu]]\n* [[Lakshadweep]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n** [[Indian local government response to the 2020 coronavirus pandemic]]\n** [[Economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n** [[2020 India coronavirus lockdown]]\n* [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n** [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia]]\n*** [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Asia]]\n*** [[SAARC COVID-19 Emergency Fund]]\n* [[2020 stock market crash]]\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|India|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.mygov.in/covid-19 COVID-19] on [[MyGov.in]] \u2013 Government's portal for COVID-19\n* {{YouTube|playlist=PL1a9DHjZmejE-Ep2PAu2OR8HBfLP0BLIk|title=}} \u2013 COVID-19 Management videos by the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare]]\n* {{Cite book|last=Prasad|first=R.|url=https://creatives.thehindu.com/covid_19_ebook.pdf|title=The Pandemic Notebook|last2=Perappadan|first2=Bindu Shajan|last3=Shelar|first3=Jyoti|publisher=The Hindu|year=2020|isbn=|editor-last=George|editor-first=P.J.|location=|pages=|quote=A handy guide from The Hindu on understanding the coronavirus pandemic and staying protected against COVID-19}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India| ]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|India]]\n[[Category:2020 in India|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in India]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Remove leading zero from dates", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_India"}
{"title_page": "Hamantash", "text_new": "{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Hamantash\n| image            = Mohn hamantaschen.jpg\n| caption          = Mohn (poppyseed) hamantash.\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[Ashkenazi Jewish]] communities\n| region           = \n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = [[Cookie]] or [[pastry]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = \n| variations       = Filling: traditionally [[poppy seed]]\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n| no_commons       = \n}}\n\nA '''hamantash''' (pl. '''''hamantashen'''''; {{lang-yi|\u05d4\u05de\u05df\u05be\u05d8\u05d0\u05b7\u05e9}} ''homentash'', pl. {{lang|yi|\u05d4\u05de\u05df\u05be\u05d8\u05d0\u05b7\u05e9\u05df}} ''homentashn'', literally 'Haman pockets') is an [[Ashkenazi Jewish cuisine|Ashkenazi Jewish]] triangular filled-pocket [[cookie]], usually associated with the [[Jewish]] holiday of [[Purim]]. The name refers to [[Haman]], the villain in the Purim story. In Hebrew, hamantashen are known as {{lang|he|\u05d0\u05d5\u05d6\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d4\u05de\u05df}}, '''''oznei Haman''''', literally 'Haman's ears'.\n\nThe shape is achieved by folding in the sides of a circular piece of dough similar to a [[shortbread]], with a filling placed in the center.  Hamantashen are made with many different fillings, which are traditionally sweet (although savory varieties have become popular as well), including [[Poppy seed filling|mohn]] ([[poppy seed]], the oldest and most traditional variety), [[lekvar]] ([[prune]] jam), nut, [[Date (fruit)|date]], [[apricot]], [[raspberry]], [[raisins]], [[apple]], vanilla [[pastry cream]] with [[chocolate chips]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads |publisher=Artisan Books}}</ref> [[cherry]], [[Common fig|fig]], [[chocolate]], [[dulce de leche]], [[halva]], or even [[caramel]] or [[cheese]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.epicurious.com/features/news/dailydish/031306 |title=Epi Log: The latest in Food News, the Culinary Arts & Cooking<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2007-03-25 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120630123404/http://www.epicurious.com/features/news/dailydish/031306 |archive-date=2012-06-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Their formation varies from hard similar to a [[shortbread]] to soft doughy casings.\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:Plate4Hamantashen.jpg|thumb|right|Four hamantashen: (clockwise from top left) chocolate, poppy seed, blueberry, and cherry.]]\nIn Yiddish, the word ''homentash'' is singular, while ''homentashen'' is the plural form. However, ''hamantashen'' is the more common word form among English speakers, even when referring to a single pastry (for example, \"I ate a poppy seed hamantashen\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sdjewishworld.com/2013/02/22/all-about-hamantaschen/|title=All about hamantaschen|last=Rosenthal|first=Leonard|date=22 February 2013|website=[[San Diego Jewish World]]|publisher=Donald H. & Nancy E. Harrison|access-date=28 September 2016|quote=...that does not stop people from using the plural even when they are referring to the singular...}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.learnreligions.com/what-are-hamantaschen-2076476|title=Why Do Jews Eat Hamentaschen During Purim?|last=Pelaia|first=Ariela|website=Learn Religions|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\n==Name and symbolism==\n''Hamantash'' is also spelled ''hamentasch'', ''homentash'', ''homentasch'', ''homentaschan'', or even ''(h)umentash''. The name ''hamantash'' is commonly viewed as a reference to [[Haman (Bible)|Haman]], the villain of [[Purim]], as described in the [[Book of Esther]]. The pastries are supposed to symbolize the defeated enemy of the Jewish people.<ref>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=613&letter=P&search=hamantaschen ''Purim, ''Jewish Encyclopedia, 1906], 'In this connection it may be mentioned that for the celebration of Purim there developed among the Jews a special kind of baking. Cakes were shaped into certain forms and were given names having some symbolic bearing on the historical events of Purim. Thus the Jews of Germany eat \"Hamantaschen\" and \"Hamanohren\" (in Italy, \"orrechi d'Aman\"), \"Kreppchen,\" \"Kindchen,\" etc.'</ref> The word ''tash'' means \"pouch\" or \"pocket\" in Yiddish, and thus may refer to ''Haman's pockets'', symbolizing the money that Haman offered to Ahasuerus in exchange for permission to destroy the Jews. In Hebrew, ''tash'' means \"weaken\", and the hamantash may celebrate the weakening of Haman and the hope that God will weaken all of the enemies of the Jews.<ref name=\"shurpin\">{{cite web |url=https://www.chabad.org/holidays/purim/article_cdo/aid/2872815/jewish/The-History-and-Meaning-of-Hamantaschen.htm |title=The History and Meaning of Hamantaschen |last=Shurpin |first=Yehuda |website=Chabad.org  |access-date=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Another possible source of the name is a [[folk etymology]]: the Yiddish word \u05de\u05d0\u05b8\u05df\u05be\u05d8\u05d0\u05b7\u05e9\u05df (''montashn'') for a traditional delicacy, literally meaning \"poppyseed pouch\",<ref>[http://www.myjewishlearning.com/holidays/Purim/TO_Purim_Home/Foods.htm MyJewishLearning.com - Holidays: Purim Foods] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302140457/http://www.myjewishlearning.com/holidays/Purim/TO_Purim_Home/Foods.htm |date=2007-03-02 }}</ref> was transformed to ''hamantaschen'', likely by association with Haman or inclusion of the Hebrew article {{transl|he|ha-}} ({{rtl-lang|he|\u05d4}}).{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} In [[Israel]], hamantaschen are called ''oznei Haman'' ({{lang-he|\u05d0\u05d5\u05d6\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d4\u05de\u05df}}), [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] for \"Haman's ears\" in reference to their defeated enemy's ears.\n\nThe reason for the three-sided shape is uncertain. There is an old legend that Haman wore a three-cornered hat.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lewinsky |first=Yom Tov |date=1958 |title=Sefer Hamoadim |pages=154|url=http://chabadlibrarybooks.com/pdfpager.aspx?req=41737&st=&pgnum=169 |access-date=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Alternatively, the [[Midrash]] says that when Haman recognized the merit of the [[Patriarchs (Bible)|Three Patriarchs]], his strength immediately weakened.<ref name=\"shurpin\"/> ''[[Naked Archaeologist]]'' documentarian [[Simcha Jacobovici]] has shown the resemblance of hamantaschen to dice from the ancient Babylonian [[Royal Game of Ur]], thus suggesting that the pastries are meant to symbolize the pyramidal shape of the dice cast by Haman in determining the day of destruction for the Jews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishindependent.ca/archives/april11/archives11april08-02.html |title=Filmmaker unearths mystery |last1=Gordon |first1=Dave |date=April 8, 2011 |website=Jewish Independent |accessdate=March 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140314133528/http://www.jewishindependent.ca/archives/april11/archives11april08-02.html |archivedate=March 14, 2014 }}</ref> A simpler explanation is that the shape derives from traditional Jewish baking techniques in Central Europe for folding dough so as to form a pouch around a filling, also common for making dumplings.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} It has also been suggested that the shape is a representation of female reproductive organs, and that the poppy-seed filling is a fertility symbol.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schnur |first1=Susan |title=From Prenistoric Cave Art To Your Cookie Pan: Tracing The Hamantasch Herstory |journal=Lilith |date=Spring 1998 |volume=23 |issue=1 |pages=22-4 |url=https://lilith.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/v23i01_Spring_1998-08.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kaplan |first1=Arielle |title=Yes, There\u2019s a Reason Hamantaschen Look Like Vaginas |url=https://www.heyalma.com/yes-theres-a-reason-hamantaschen-look-like-vaginas/ |website=Alma |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Sweet fillings==\nSweet hamantaschen fillings range from the traditional such as [[Poppy seed filling|mohn]]/poppy seed, [[prune|lekvar]]/prune, [[apricot jam]], and also date which is especially popular in Israel.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads}}</ref> \n\n===Prune===\nPrune hamantaschen was invented in 1731 by David Brandeis of [[Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav|Jung-Bunzlau]], [[Bohemia]]. The daughter of a Christian bookbinder purchased from Brandeis povidl (plum jam) which she claimed had made her family ill; as her father coincidentally died a few days after eating it. The [[burgomaster]] of the city ordered the closure of Brandeis' store and imprisoned him, his wife, and son for selling poisonous food to Christians. Investigations by municipal authorities and the court of appeal in Prague revealed that the bookbinder had died of [[Tuberculosis|consumption]] and the charges were dismissed. Brandeis wrote a scroll which he called ''Shir HaMa'alot l'David'' (\"A [[Song of Ascents]] to David\"), to be read on 10 Adar, accompanied by a festive meal. He was freed from prison four days before Purim after the charges against him were proven to be false, and in celebration of his release, Jews from his city celebrated with povidl or plum hamantaschen.\n<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sacharin |first1=Emily |title=A Purim Classic: Sugar Cookie Hamantaschen |url=https://www.poppyandprune.com/2018/02/12/purim-classic-sugar-cookie-hamantaschen/ |website=Poppy and Prune |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Purims, Special |url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/12450-purims-special#anchor26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304204004/http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/12450-purims-special#anchor26 |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 March 2016 |website=Jewish Encyclopedia |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Vanilla pastry cream with chocolate chips===\n\n[[File:Hamantashen.jpg|thumb|right|Hamantash filled with vanilla pastry cream and chocolate chips prior to baking.]]\n\nIsraeli baker Uri Scheft offers hamantaschen filled with a vanilla [[custard|pastry cream]] and chocolate chips at Lehamim/Breads Bakery, his bakeries in [[Tel Aviv]] and [[New York City]]. A recipe for this filling is also featured in Scheft's cookbook.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads}}</ref>\n\n==Savory fillings==\nSavory hamantaschen fillings have emerged in recent years, and their popularity has grown and are commonly prepared at home but can also be found in various Jewish bakeries and restaurants serving Jewish cuisine. Savory varieties may have fillings such as [[pizza]], spinach and feta, lamb, potato, or cheese, and are often somewhat similar to other [[Jewish cuisine|Jewish]] pastries such as the [[knish]], [[bourekas]], and sambusak.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sarna |first1=Shannon |title=The Modern Jewish Baker}}</ref>\n\n==Preparation==\n\n[[File:Flickr - Israel Defense Forces - IDF Soldiers Volunteer for Purim with Bereaved Families of Fallen Soldiers (1).jpg|thumb|right|Volunteers in Israel preparing hamantaschen for Purim with the children of fallen soldiers.]]\n\n[[File:Hamantaschen.jpg|thumb|right|Poppy seed hamantaschen prior to baking.]]\n\nSweet hamantaschen are typically made with a dough containing butter or, less-commmonly a [[pareve]] dough containing oil. Depending on the ingredients used in the dough, the consistency of the finished hamantaschen can range from dry and crumbly like to a [[shortbread]], to soft and cakey like a [[black and white cookie]], to firm and crisp like a butter cookie. The dough is generally prepared with flour, eggs, sugar, butter (or margarine or cooking oil), and a flavoring such as vanilla (or sometimes [[Cocoa bean|cocoa]], [[rose water]], or [[orange blossom water]] may be used); sometimes milk is used in the dough, and sometimes a leavener such as baking powder or baking soda is added as well. The dough is then mixed gently so as to incorporate all the ingredients together but not make the dough tough and give the hamantaschen an inferior texture.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hamantaschen Purim Dresden (1).JPG|thumb|right|Hamantaschen served at a Purim party in Dresden that have been dusted with powdered sugar.]]\n\nThe dough is allowed to rest in the refrigerator and is then removed and rolled out to a thickness of between 1/8 and 1/4 of an inch; rounds of dough are stamped out and are often brushed with an [[egg wash]] to encourage sealing prior to the addition of the filling. The most popular filling is [[poppyseed]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads}}</ref>, but apricot, prune, strawberry, raspberry, chocolate, [[peanut butter and jelly]], and others are also common. The bottom and the top two corners of the dough are folded inward but do not fully enclose the filling, allowing it to remain visible. Sometimes hamantaschen may be frozen for a short period of time after shaping in order to prevent leakage of the filling. Then they are baked in an oven at medium heat for a short duration of time. Sometimes after baking hamantaschen may be dusted with [[confectioner's sugar]], dipped in [[melted chocolate]], or topped with [[sprinkles]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nathan |first1=Joan |title=The Jewish Holiday Cookbook}}</ref>\n\nSavory hamantaschen are prepared in much the same way as sweet hamantaschen, with the exception of the fillings; and they are generally made with a different dough, such one similar to a [[pie]] crust or [[puff pastry]], or a modified sweet hamantaschen dough containing less sugar.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sarna |first1=Shannon |title=The Modern Jewish Baker}}</ref>\n\n==Hamantashen in Israel==\n\n[[File:Purim In Mahne Yehuda.jpg|thumb|right|Bakers selling hamantaschen as part of Purim celebrations at [[Machne Yehuda]] in [[Jerusalem, Israel]].]]\n\n{{blockquote|\"In recent years, Israeli bakeries have increasingly offered gourmet versions of the three-cornered cookie \u2014 marzipan, say, or gluten-free varieties \u2014 alongside the classics, like poppyseed. The change reflects the growing sophistication of Israel\u2019s culinary scene, which is focused on updating traditional dishes and fusing them with cuisines from around the world.\"|Andrew Tobin|''[[The Times of Israel]]''<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tobin |first1=Andrew |title=Israeli chefs take hamantaschen to a whole new level |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-chefs-take-hamantaschen-to-a-whole-new-level/ |accessdate=15 March 2020 |agency=The Times of Israel}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Flickr - Israel Defense Forces - IDF Logistics Branch Celebrates Purim (1).jpg|thumb|right|Hamantaschen baked by members of the [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] [[Logistics Corps]] as part of a baking competition hosted by a winner of the [[Masterchef Israel]] television series.]]\nHamantaschen are known as ''\"oznei haman\"'' in Israel, and are the most popular cookie sold at bakeries across Israel in the weeks leading up to the celebration of Purim each year, with both large chains and small independent bakeries offering many different varieties. As in the [[Jewish diaspora|diaspora]], [[Poppy seed filling|poppyseed]] remains the most-popular filling, with chocolate in second, and date filling coming in third in popularity. Jam is not nearly as common a filling as in America.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tobin |first1=Andrew |title=Israeli chefs take hamantaschen to a whole new level |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-chefs-take-hamantaschen-to-a-whole-new-level/ |accessdate=15 March 2020 |agency=The Times of Israel}}</ref> \n\nEach year bakeries offer new, innovative flavors of hamantaschen. Roladin, a popular Israeli bakery chain offers oznei haman with fillings such as goat cheese and onion jam, [[amaretto]]-pistachio-marzipan, and [[triple-sec]] [[cheesecake]], among others. In 2017, Roladin announced that they were launching a dozen new flavors as well as reinvented versions of the more traditional fillings, and projected that they would sell over 2 million oznei haman during the Purim season. Lehamim Bakery, which has locations in [[Tel Aviv]] and [[New York City]] offers fillings such as [[sweet potato]] and feta, [[charoset]], vanilla pastry cream with chocolate chips, apple, [[marzipan]], and others. Oren Becker, an Israeli pastry chef has started making gluten free, vegan low or no-sugar, and low fat hamantaschen, and has said his personal favorite is made with a whole grain dough and filled with [[goji berries]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tobin |first1=Andrew |title=Israeli chefs take hamantaschen to a whole new level |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-chefs-take-hamantaschen-to-a-whole-new-level/ |accessdate=15 March 2020 |agency=The Times of Israel}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Latke\u2013Hamantash Debate]]\n* [[Ashkenazi Jewish cuisine]]\n* [[Israeli cuisine]]\n* [[American Jewish cuisine]]\n* [[Culture of Israel]]\n* [[Ma'amoul]]- a similar [[Mizrahi Jewish cuisine|Mizrahi Jewish]] filled cookie traditionally served for [[Purim]]\n* [[Jam tart]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Purim Footer}}\n{{Jewish baked goods}}\n{{pastries}}\n\n[[Category:Ashkenazi Jewish cuisine]]\n[[Category:Jewish baked goods]]\n[[Category:Jewish cookies]]\n[[Category:Israeli pastries]]\n[[Category:Pastries with poppy seeds]]\n[[Category:Purim foods]]\n[[Category:Yiddish words and phrases]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Hamantash\n| image            = Mohn hamantaschen.jpg\n| caption          = Mohn (poppyseed) hamantash.\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[Ashkenazi Jewish]] communities\n| region           = \n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = [[Cookie]] or [[pastry]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = \n| variations       = Filling: traditionally [[poppy seed]]\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n| no_commons       = \n}}\n\nA '''hamantash''' (pl. '''''hamantashen'''''; {{lang-yi|\u05d4\u05de\u05df\u05be\u05d8\u05d0\u05b7\u05e9}} ''homentash'', pl. {{lang|yi|\u05d4\u05de\u05df\u05be\u05d8\u05d0\u05b7\u05e9\u05df}} ''homentashn'', literally 'Haman pockets') is an [[Ashkenazi Jewish cuisine|Ashkenazi Jewish]] triangular filled-pocket [[cookie]], usually associated with the [[Jewish]] holiday of [[Purim]]. The name refers to [[Haman]], the villain in the Purim story. In Hebrew, hamantashen are known as {{lang|he|\u05d0\u05d5\u05d6\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d4\u05de\u05df}}, '''''oznei Haman''''', literally 'Haman's ears'.\n\nThe shape is achieved by folding in the sides of a circular piece of dough similar to a [[shortbread]], with a filling placed in the center.  Hamantashen are made with many different fillings, which are traditionally sweet (although savory varieties have become popular as well), including [[Poppy seed filling|mohn]] ([[poppy seed]], the oldest and most traditional variety), [[lekvar]] ([[prune]] jam), nut, [[Date (fruit)|date]], [[apricot]], [[raspberry]], [[raisins]], [[apple]], vanilla [[pastry cream]] with [[chocolate chips]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads |publisher=Artisan Books}}</ref> [[cherry]], [[Common fig|fig]], [[chocolate]], [[dulce de leche]], [[halva]], or even [[caramel]] or [[cheese]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.epicurious.com/features/news/dailydish/031306 |title=Epi Log: The latest in Food News, the Culinary Arts & Cooking<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2007-03-25 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120630123404/http://www.epicurious.com/features/news/dailydish/031306 |archive-date=2012-06-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Their formation varies from hard similar to a [[shortbread]] to soft doughy casings.\n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:Plate4Hamantashen.jpg|thumb|right|Four hamantashen: (clockwise from top left) chocolate, poppy seed, blueberry, and cherry.]]\nIn Yiddish, the word ''homentash'' is singular, while ''homentashen'' is the plural form. However, ''hamantashen'' is the more common word form among English speakers, even when referring to a single pastry (for example, \"I ate a poppy seed hamantashen\").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sdjewishworld.com/2013/02/22/all-about-hamantaschen/|title=All about hamantaschen|last=Rosenthal|first=Leonard|date=22 February 2013|website=[[San Diego Jewish World]]|publisher=Donald H. & Nancy E. Harrison|access-date=28 September 2016|quote=...that does not stop people from using the plural even when they are referring to the singular...}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.learnreligions.com/what-are-hamantaschen-2076476|title=Why Do Jews Eat Hamentaschen During Purim?|last=Pelaia|first=Ariela|website=Learn Religions|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\n==Name and symbolism==\n''Hamantash'' is also spelled ''hamentasch'', ''homentash'', ''homentasch'', ''homentaschan'', or even ''(h)umentash''. The name ''hamantash'' is commonly viewed as a reference to [[Haman (Bible)|Haman]], the villain of [[Purim]], as described in the [[Book of Esther]]. The pastries are supposed to symbolize the defeated enemy of the Jewish people.<ref>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=613&letter=P&search=hamantaschen ''Purim, ''Jewish Encyclopedia, 1906], 'In this connection it may be mentioned that for the celebration of Purim there developed among the Jews a special kind of baking. Cakes were shaped into certain forms and were given names having some symbolic bearing on the historical events of Purim. Thus the Jews of Germany eat \"Hamantaschen\" and \"Hamanohren\" (in Italy, \"orrechi d'Aman\"), \"Kreppchen,\" \"Kindchen,\" etc.'</ref> The word ''tash'' means \"pouch\" or \"pocket\" in Yiddish, and thus may refer to ''Haman's pockets'', symbolizing the money that Haman offered to Ahasuerus in exchange for permission to destroy the Jews. In Hebrew, ''tash'' means \"weaken\", and the hamantash may celebrate the weakening of Haman and the hope that God will weaken all of the enemies of the Jews.<ref name=\"shurpin\">{{cite web |url=https://www.chabad.org/holidays/purim/article_cdo/aid/2872815/jewish/The-History-and-Meaning-of-Hamantaschen.htm |title=The History and Meaning of Hamantaschen |last=Shurpin |first=Yehuda |website=Chabad.org  |access-date=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Another possible source of the name is a [[folk etymology]]: the Yiddish word \u05de\u05d0\u05b8\u05df\u05be\u05d8\u05d0\u05b7\u05e9\u05df (''montashn'') for a traditional delicacy, literally meaning \"poppyseed pouch\",<ref>[http://www.myjewishlearning.com/holidays/Purim/TO_Purim_Home/Foods.htm MyJewishLearning.com - Holidays: Purim Foods] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070302140457/http://www.myjewishlearning.com/holidays/Purim/TO_Purim_Home/Foods.htm |date=2007-03-02 }}</ref> was transformed to ''hamantaschen'', likely by association with Haman or inclusion of the Hebrew article {{transl|he|ha-}} ({{rtl-lang|he|\u05d4}}).{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} In [[Israel]], hamantaschen are called ''oznei Haman'' ({{lang-he|\u05d0\u05d5\u05d6\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d4\u05de\u05df}}), [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] for \"Haman's ears\" in reference to their defeated enemy's ears.\n\nThe reason for the three-sided shape is uncertain. There is an old legend that Haman wore a three-cornered hat.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lewinsky |first=Yom Tov |date=1958 |title=Sefer Hamoadim |pages=154|url=http://chabadlibrarybooks.com/pdfpager.aspx?req=41737&st=&pgnum=169 |access-date=March 2, 2018}}</ref> Alternatively, the [[Midrash]] says that when Haman recognized the merit of the [[Patriarchs (Bible)|Three Patriarchs]], his strength immediately weakened.<ref name=\"shurpin\"/> ''[[Naked Archaeologist]]'' documentarian [[Simcha Jacobovici]] has shown the resemblance of hamantaschen to dice from the ancient Babylonian [[Royal Game of Ur]], thus suggesting that the pastries are meant to symbolize the pyramidal shape of the dice cast by Haman in determining the day of destruction for the Jews.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishindependent.ca/archives/april11/archives11april08-02.html |title=Filmmaker unearths mystery |last1=Gordon |first1=Dave |date=April 8, 2011 |website=Jewish Independent |accessdate=March 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140314133528/http://www.jewishindependent.ca/archives/april11/archives11april08-02.html |archivedate=March 14, 2014 }}</ref> A simpler explanation is that the shape derives from traditional Jewish baking techniques in Central Europe for folding dough so as to form a pouch around a filling, also common for making dumplings.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}} It has also been suggested that the shape is a representation of female reproductive organs, and that the poppy-seed filling is a fertility symbol.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schnur |first1=Susan |title=From Prenistoric Cave Art To Your Cookie Pan: Tracing The Hamantasch Herstory |journal=Lilith |date=Spring 1998 |volume=23 |issue=1 |pages=22-4 |url=https://lilith.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/v23i01_Spring_1998-08.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Kaplan |first1=Arielle |title=Yes, There\u2019s a Reason Hamantaschen Look Like Vaginas |url=https://www.heyalma.com/yes-theres-a-reason-hamantaschen-look-like-vaginas/ |website=Alma |accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Sweet fillings==\nSweet hamantaschen fillings range from the traditional such as [[Poppy seed filling|mohn]]/poppy seed, [[prune|lekvar]]/prune, [[apricot jam]], and also date which is especially popular in Israel.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads}}</ref> \n\n===Prune===\nPrune hamantaschen was invented in 1731 by David Brandeis of [[Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav|Jung-Bunzlau]], [[Bohemia]]. The daughter of a Christian bookbinder purchased from Brandeis povidl (plum jam) which she claimed had made her family ill; as her father coincidentally died a few days after eating it. The [[burgomaster]] of the city ordered the closure of Brandeis' store and imprisoned him, his wife, and son for selling poisonous food to Christians. Investigations by municipal authorities and the court of appeal in Prague revealed that the bookbinder had died of [[Tuberculosis|consumption]] and the charges were dismissed. Brandeis wrote a scroll which he called ''Shir HaMa'alot l'David'' (\"A [[Song of Ascents]] to David\"), to be read on 10 Adar, accompanied by a festive meal. He was freed from prison four days before Purim after the charges against him were proven to be false, and in celebration of his release, Jews from his city celebrated with povidl or plum hamantaschen.\n<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sacharin |first1=Emily |title=A Purim Classic: Sugar Cookie Hamantaschen |url=https://www.poppyandprune.com/2018/02/12/purim-classic-sugar-cookie-hamantaschen/ |website=Poppy and Prune |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Purims, Special |url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/12450-purims-special#anchor26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304204004/http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/12450-purims-special#anchor26 |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 March 2016 |website=Jewish Encyclopedia |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Vanilla pastry cream with chocolate chips===\n\n[[File:Hamantashen.jpg|thumb|right|Hamantash filled with vanilla pastry cream and chocolate chips prior to baking.]]\n\nIsraeli baker Uri Scheft offers hamantaschen filled with a vanilla [[custard|pastry cream]] and chocolate chips at Lehamim/Breads Bakery, his bakeries in [[Tel Aviv]] and [[New York City]]. A recipe for this filling is also featured in Scheft's cookbook.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads}}</ref>\n\n==Savory fillings==\nSavory hamantaschen fillings have emerged in recent years, and their popularity has grown and are commonly prepared at home but can also be found in various Jewish bakeries and restaurants serving Jewish cuisine. Savory varieties may have fillings such as [[pizza]], spinach and feta, lamb, potato, or cheese, and are often somewhat similar to other [[Jewish cuisine|Jewish]] pastries such as the [[knish]], [[bourekas]], and sambusak.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sarna |first1=Shannon |title=The Modern Jewish Baker}}</ref>\n\n==Preparation==\n\n[[File:Flickr - Israel Defense Forces - IDF Soldiers Volunteer for Purim with Bereaved Families of Fallen Soldiers (1).jpg|thumb|right|Volunteers in Israel preparing hamantaschen for Purim with the children of fallen soldiers.]]\n\n[[File:Hamantaschen.jpg|thumb|right|Poppy seed hamantaschen prior to baking.]]\n\nSweet hamantaschen are typically made with a dough containing butter or, less-commmonly a [[pareve]] dough containing oil. Depending on the ingredients used in the dough, the consistency of the finished hamantaschen can range from dry and crumbly like to a [[shortbread]], to soft and cakey like a [[black and white cookie]], to firm and crisp like a butter cookie. The dough is generally prepared with flour, eggs, sugar, butter (or margarine or cooking oil), and a flavoring such as vanilla (or sometimes [[cocoa]], [[rose water]], or [[orange blossom water]] may be used); sometimes milk is used in the dough, and sometimes a leavener such as baking powder or baking soda is added as well. The dough is then mixed gently so as to incorporate all the ingredients together but not make the dough tough and give the hamantaschen an inferior texture.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hamantaschen Purim Dresden (1).JPG|thumb|right|Hamantaschen served at a Purim party in Dresden that have been dusted with powdered sugar.]]\n\nThe dough is allowed to rest in the refrigerator and is then removed and rolled out to a thickness of between 1/8 and 1/4 of an inch; rounds of dough are stamped out and are often brushed with an [[egg wash]] to encourage sealing prior to the addition of the filling. The most popular filling is [[poppyseed]]<ref>{{cite book |last1=Scheft |first1=Uri |title=Breaking Breads}}</ref>, but apricot, prune, strawberry, raspberry, chocolate, [[peanut butter and jelly]], and others are also common. The bottom and the top two corners of the dough are folded inward but do not fully enclose the filling, allowing it to remain visible. Sometimes hamantaschen may be frozen for a short period of time after shaping in order to prevent leakage of the filling. Then they are baked in an oven at medium heat for a short duration of time. Sometimes after baking hamantaschen may be dusted with [[confectioner's sugar]], dipped in [[melted chocolate]], or topped with [[sprinkles]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nathan |first1=Joan |title=The Jewish Holiday Cookbook}}</ref>\n\nSavory hamantaschen are prepared in much the same way as sweet hamantaschen, with the exception of the fillings; and they are generally made with a different dough, such one similar to a [[pie]] crust or [[puff pastry]], or a modified sweet hamantaschen dough containing less sugar.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Sarna |first1=Shannon |title=The Modern Jewish Baker}}</ref>\n\n==Hamantashen in Israel==\n\n[[File:Purim In Mahne Yehuda.jpg|thumb|right|Bakers selling hamantaschen as part of Purim celebrations at [[Machne Yehuda]] in [[Jerusalem, Israel]].]]\n\n{{blockquote|\"In recent years, Israeli bakeries have increasingly offered gourmet versions of the three-cornered cookie \u2014 marzipan, say, or gluten-free varieties \u2014 alongside the classics, like poppyseed. The change reflects the growing sophistication of Israel\u2019s culinary scene, which is focused on updating traditional dishes and fusing them with cuisines from around the world.\"|Andrew Tobin|''[[The Times of Israel]]''<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tobin |first1=Andrew |title=Israeli chefs take hamantaschen to a whole new level |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-chefs-take-hamantaschen-to-a-whole-new-level/ |accessdate=15 March 2020 |agency=The Times of Israel}}</ref>}}\n\n[[File:Flickr - Israel Defense Forces - IDF Logistics Branch Celebrates Purim (1).jpg|thumb|right|Hamantaschen baked by members of the [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] [[Logistics Corps]] as part of a baking competition hosted by a winner of the [[Masterchef Israel]] television series.]]\nHamantaschen are known as ''\"oznei haman\"'' in Israel, and are the most popular cookie sold at bakeries across Israel in the weeks leading up to the celebration of Purim each year, with both large chains and small independent bakeries offering many different varieties. As in the [[Jewish diaspora|diaspora]], [[Poppy seed filling|poppyseed]] remains the most-popular filling, with chocolate in second, and date filling coming in third in popularity. Jam is not nearly as common a filling as in America.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tobin |first1=Andrew |title=Israeli chefs take hamantaschen to a whole new level |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-chefs-take-hamantaschen-to-a-whole-new-level/ |accessdate=15 March 2020 |agency=The Times of Israel}}</ref> \n\nEach year bakeries offer new, innovative flavors of hamantaschen. Roladin, a popular Israeli bakery chain offers oznei haman with fillings such as goat cheese and onion jam, [[amaretto]]-pistachio-marzipan, and [[triple-sec]] [[cheesecake]], among others. In 2017, Roladin announced that they were launching a dozen new flavors as well as reinvented versions of the more traditional fillings, and projected that they would sell over 2 million oznei haman during the Purim season. Lehamim Bakery, which has locations in [[Tel Aviv]] and [[New York City]] offers fillings such as [[sweet potato]] and feta, [[charoset]], vanilla pastry cream with chocolate chips, apple, [[marzipan]], and others. Oren Becker, an Israeli pastry chef has started making gluten free, vegan low or no-sugar, and low fat hamantaschen, and has said his personal favorite is made with a whole grain dough and filled with [[goji berries]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tobin |first1=Andrew |title=Israeli chefs take hamantaschen to a whole new level |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/israeli-chefs-take-hamantaschen-to-a-whole-new-level/ |accessdate=15 March 2020 |agency=The Times of Israel}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Latke\u2013Hamantash Debate]]\n* [[Ashkenazi Jewish cuisine]]\n* [[Israeli cuisine]]\n* [[American Jewish cuisine]]\n* [[Culture of Israel]]\n* [[Ma'amoul]]- a similar [[Mizrahi Jewish cuisine|Mizrahi Jewish]] filled cookie traditionally served for [[Purim]]\n* [[Jam tart]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Purim Footer}}\n{{Jewish baked goods}}\n{{pastries}}\n\n[[Category:Ashkenazi Jewish cuisine]]\n[[Category:Jewish baked goods]]\n[[Category:Jewish cookies]]\n[[Category:Israeli pastries]]\n[[Category:Pastries with poppy seeds]]\n[[Category:Purim foods]]\n[[Category:Yiddish words and phrases]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toCocoa(link changed toCocoa bean) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hamantash"}
{"title_page": "The Aristocats", "text_new": "{{short description|1970 American animated film produced by Walt Disney Productions}}\n{{distinguish|The Aristocrats}}\n{{pp-semi-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Expand French|Les Aristochats|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name        = The Aristocats\n| image       = aristoposter.jpg\n| caption     = Original theatrical release poster\n| director    = [[Wolfgang Reitherman]]\n| producer    = [[Winston Hibler]]<br/>Wolfgang Reitherman\n| story       = [[Ken Anderson (animator)|Ken Anderson]]<br/>Larry Clemmons<br/>Eric Cleworth<br/>Vance Gerry<br/>Julius Svendsen<br/>[[Frank Thomas (animator)|Frank Thomas]]<br/>[[Ralph Wright]]\n| based on    = \"The Aristocats\" by Tom McGowan and Tom Rowe \n| studio      = [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Walt Disney Productions]]\n| distributor = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Distribution]]\n| music       = [[George Bruns]]\n| starring    = [[Phil Harris]]<br/>[[Eva Gabor]]<br/>[[Hermione Baddeley]]<br/>[[Gary Dubin]]<br/>[[#Cast|Dean Clark]]<br/>[[Sterling Holloway]]<br/>[[Roddy Maude-Roxby]]<br/>[[Louise English|Liz English]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1970|12|11|premiere|1970|12|24|United States}} <!-- First and Country of Origin releases per WP:FILMRELEASE. -->\n| runtime     = 79 minutes\n| country     = United States\n| language    = English\n| budget      = $4 million<ref>{{cite news|last=Scott|first=Vernon|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42762710/the_logansport_press/|title=News from Hollywood|newspaper=[[Pharos-Tribune|The Logansport Press]]|page=6|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|date=February 17, 1971|accessdate=January 21, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n| gross       = $191 million<ref name=\"DisneyWW\">{{cite magazine|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|title=Cartoon Coffers - Top-Grossing Disney Animated Features at the Worldwide B.O.|date=October 27, 2003|page=6}}</ref>}}\n\n'''''The Aristocats''''' is a 1970 American animated [[Romance film|romantic]] [[Adventure film|adventure]] [[Musical film|musical]] [[Comedy film|comedy]] film directed by [[Wolfgang Reitherman]]. It was produced by [[Walt Disney Productions]] and released by [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Distribution]]. The 20th [[List of Walt Disney Animation Studios films|Disney animated feature film]], the film is based on a story by Tom McGowan and Tom Rowe, and revolves around a family of [[Aristocracy (class)|aristocrat]]ic cats, and how an alley cat acquaintance helps them after a [[butler]] has kidnapped them to gain his mistress's fortune which was intended to go to them. The film features the voices of [[Eva Gabor]], [[Hermione Baddeley]], [[Phil Harris]], Dean Clark, [[Sterling Holloway]], [[Scatman Crothers]], and [[Roddy Maude-Roxby]].\n\nIn 1962, ''The Aristocats'' project began as an original script for a two-part live-action episode for ''[[Walt Disney anthology television series#Walt Disney.27s Wonderful World of Color .281961.E2.80.931969.29|Walt Disney's Wonderful World of Color]]'', developed by writers Tom McGowan and Tom Rowe and producer Harry Tytle. Following two years of re-writes, [[Walt Disney]] suggested the project would be more suitable for an animated film, and placed the project in [[Turnaround (filmmaking)|turnaround]] as ''[[The Jungle Book (1967 film)|The Jungle Book]]'' advanced into production. When ''The Jungle Book'' was nearly complete, Disney appointed [[Ken Anderson (animator)|Ken Anderson]] to develop preliminary work on ''The Aristocats'', making it the last film project to be approved by Disney personally before his death in December 1966.\n\n''The Aristocats'' was released on December 24, 1970 to positive reception and was a box office success.\n\n==Plot==\n<!--Per WP:FILMPLOT, plot length should be between 400 and 700 words. Current count is 483 words.-->\n\nIn [[Paris, France|Paris]] 1910, mother cat Duchess and her three [[kitten]]s, Berlioz, Marie, and Toulouse, live with retired opera diva Madame Adelaide Bonfamille, and her English butler, Edgar. One day while preparing her [[will (law)|will]] with lawyer Georges Hautecourt, Madame declares her fortune to be left to her cats until their deaths, and thereafter to Edgar. Edgar hears this through a [[speaking tube]] and plots to eliminate the cats. Therefore, he sedates the cats by putting [[sleeping pills]] in a milk mixture intended for them, and enters the countryside to abandon them. There, he is ambushed by two [[hound]]s named Napoleon and Lafayette, and the cats are stranded in the countryside, while Madame Adelaide, Roquefort the mouse and Frou-Frou the horse discover their absence.\n\nIn the morning, Duchess meets an alley cat named Thomas O'Malley, who offers to guide her and the kittens to Paris. The group briefly [[hitchhiking|hitchhikes]] in a milk truck before being chased off by the driver. Later, while crossing a railroad trestle, the cats narrowly avoid an oncoming train, but Marie falls into a river and is saved by O'Malley, who in turn has to be rescued himself by two English geese, Amelia and Abigail Gabble, who accompany the cats to Paris. Edgar returns to the country to retrieve his possessions from Napoleon and Lafayette, as the only evidence that could incriminate him.\n\nTravelling across the rooftops of the city, the cats meet O'Malley's friend Scat Cat and his musicians, who perform the song \"Ev'rybody Wants to Be a Cat\". After the band has departed, O'Malley and Duchess converse on a nearby rooftop while the kittens listen at a windowsill. Here, Duchess' loyalty to Madame prompts her to decline O'Malley's proposal of marriage. Duchess and the kittens return to Madame's mansion, but Edgar places them in a sack and prepares to ship them to [[Timbuktu]]; They direct Roquefort to retrieve O'Malley. He does so, and O'Malley returns to the mansion, instructing Roquefort to find Scat Cat and his gang. The alley cats and Frou-Frou fight Edgar, while Roquefort frees Duchess and the kittens. At the end of the fight, Edgar is locked in his own packing-case and sent to Timbuktu himself, never to be seen again. Madame Adelaide's will is rewritten to exclude Edgar, with Madame remaining ignorant of the reason for Edgar's departure. After adopting O\u2019Malley into the family, Madame establishes a charity foundation housing Paris' stray cats (represented by Scat Cat and his band, who reprise their song).\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Eva Gabor]] as Duchess \u2013 Madame Adelaide's [[cat]] and mother of three [[kittens]], forced to choose between loyalty to Madame and her own attachment to Thomas O'Malley at the end of the film. [[Robie Lester]] provided the singing voice for Duchess.\n* [[Phil Harris]] as Thomas O'Malley (full name: Abraham de Lacy Giuseppe Casey Thomas O'Malley) \u2013 A [[feral cat]] who befriends Duchess and her kittens, becoming a father figure to the kittens and falling in love with Duchess. For cultural reasons, the [[Italian language|Italian]] dubbing of the film changes him to \u201cRomeo, er mejo der Colosseo\u201d ([[Roman dialect]] for \"The best [cat] of the [[Colosseum]]\"), an Italian cat from [[Rome]] speaking with a strong Roman accent. O'Malley is a cat from Rome in the Italian dub because In Italy, it was widely known that until recent times there were lots of Alley Cats in the Colosseum.\n* [[Gary Dubin]] as Toulouse \u2013 the oldest kitten, who idolizes all alley cats and especially Thomas. He is also a talented painter and is loosely based on French painter [[Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec]].\n* [[Louise English|Liz English]] as Marie \u2013 middle kitten; often imperious or snobbish to her brothers, but her mother's special companion. Something of a singer.\n* Dean Clark as Berlioz \u2013 the youngest kitten. He is somewhat timid and shy, named after the French composer [[Hector Berlioz]]. This Berlioz is a talented pianist.\n* [[Roddy Maude-Roxby]] as Edgar Balthazar \u2013 Madame Adelaide's [[dim-witted]] [[butler]] who tries to get rid of the cats in order to inherit her fortune.\n* [[Scatman Crothers]] as Scat Cat \u2013 Thomas' best friend and leader of a gang of [[jazz]]-playing [[alley cats]]. Scat Cat plays the trumpet.\n* [[Paul Winchell]] as Shun Gon \u2013 a [[Siamese cat|Chinese cat]] in Scat Cat's gang. Plays the piano and drums that are made out of pots.\n* [[Lord Tim Hudson]] as Hit Cat \u2013 an English cat in Scat Cat's gang. Plays acoustic guitar.\n* [[Vito Scotti]] as Peppo \u2013 an Italian cat in Scat Cat's gang. Plays the accordion.\n* [[Thurl Ravenscroft]] as Billy Boss \u2013 a Russian cat in Scat Cat's gang. Plays the double bass.\n* [[Sterling Holloway]] as Roquefort \u2013 A house mouse and also a friend of the cats, who assists in the expulsion of Edgar.\n* [[Pat Buttram]] as Napoleon \u2013 a [[Bloodhound]] who attacks Edgar when he intrudes in the farm where Napoleon lives. Napoleon insists, whenever cohort Lafayette makes a suggestion, that he is in command, then adopts Lafayette's suggestion as his own.\n* [[George Lindsey]] as Lafayette \u2013 a [[Basset Hound]] and Napoleon's companion. He sometimes proves smarter than Napoleon, but is also more timid.\n* [[Hermione Baddeley]] as Madame Adelaide Bonfamille \u2013 a former [[opera singer]] and [[owner]] of Duchess and her kittens.\n* [[Charles Lane (actor)|Charles Lane]] as Georges Hautecourt \u2013 Madame Bonfamille's [[lawyer]]: an eccentric, lively old man\n* [[Nancy Kulp]] as Frou-Frou \u2013 Roquefort's horse companion, who subdues Edgar. [[Ruth Buzzi]] provided her singing voice.\n* [[Monica Evans]] as Abigail Gabble \u2013 a [[goose]] who befriends the cats.\n* [[Carole Shelley]] as Amelia Gabble \u2013 Abigail's twin sister.\n* [[Bill Thompson (voice actor)|Bill Thompson]] as Uncle Waldo \u2013 the drunken gander uncle of Abigail and Amelia.\n* [[Peter Renaday]] as French Milkman/Le Petit Cafe Cook/Truck Movers (uncredited)\n\n==Production==\n\n===Story development===\nOn December 9, 1961, Walt Disney suggested that Harry Tytle and Tom McGowan find some animal stories to adapt as a two-part live-action episode for the ''[[Walt Disney anthology television series#Walt Disney.27s Wonderful World of Color .281961.E2.80.931969.29|Wonderful World of Color]]'' television program. By New Year's 1962, McGowan had found several stories including a children's book about a mother cat and her kittens set in New York City. However, Tytle felt that a [[London]] location had added a significant element to ''[[One Hundred and One Dalmatians]]'' and suggested setting the story of the cats in Paris.<ref name=\"mouseplanet\">{{cite web|last=Sampson|first=Wade|title=The Secret Origin of the Aristocats|url=https://www.mouseplanet.com/9084/The_Secret_Origin_of_the_Aristocats|publisher=Mouse Planet|date=December 23, 2009|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> Following a rough storyline, the story became about two servants\u2014a butler and a maid\u2014who were in line to inherit a fortune of an eccentric mistress after the pet cats died and focused on their feeble and foolish attempts to eliminate the felines. [[Boris Karloff]] and [[Francoise Rosay]] were in mind to portray the butler and the distressed Madame.{{sfn|Koenig|1997|p=141}} A subplot centered around a mother cat hiding her kittens to keep them out of danger in a variety of different homes and locales around Paris, France. During the filming of ''[[Escapade in Florence]]'', McGowan brought him the story that had been written by Tom Rowe, an American writer who was living in Paris.<ref name=\"mouseplanet\" />\n\n[[File:Phil Harris 1956.JPG|thumb|right|150px|Before his death in 1966, Walt Disney contacted Phil Harris (pictured here) to voice Thomas O'Malley.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=336&dat=19801208&id=SfVSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ToMDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7155,2696962&hl=en||title=An encore purr-formance for 'The Aristocats'|last=Pearson|first=Howard|newspaper=[[Deseret News]]|via=[[Google News Archive]]|date=December 8, 1980|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref>]]\n\nBy August 1962, they sent the completed script to Burbank, where it was returned as \"rejected\" by an unknown executive at the Disney studios. Nevertheless, Tytle brought the script to Disney staying at the [[Connaught Hall, London|Connaught]] in London. Disney approved for the draft, but recommended additional cuts which were made by February 1963. Before filming was to commence, Rowe wrote a letter to Disney addressing his displeasure of the script revisions, in which Tytle responded to Rowe that the changes Disney approved of would be kept. However, by summer 1963, the project was shelved, where Tytle, in a discussion with Walt, recommended to produce ''The Aristocats'' as an animated feature.<ref name=\"mouseplanet\" /> For that reason, Disney temporarily shelved the project as the animation department was occupied with ''[[The Jungle Book (1967 film)|The Jungle Book]]''.<ref name=\"Ottawa\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2194&dat=19701218&id=kr0yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XO0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=2560,1843732&hl=en|title=The Aristocats for Christmas|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|via=Google News Archive|date=December 18, 1970|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> Meanwhile, director [[Wolfgang Reitherman]] learned of the project and suggested it as a follow-up project to ''Jungle Book''.<ref name=jimhill /> Because of the production delays, Tytle was advised to centralize his efforts on [[Live action|live action projects]] and was replaced by [[Winston Hibler]].<ref name=\"mouseplanet\" />\n\nIn 1966, Disney assigned [[Ken Anderson (animator)|Ken Anderson]] to determine whether ''Aristocats'' would be suitable for an animated feature. With occasional guidance from Reitherman, Anderson worked from scratch and simplified the two stories into a story that focused more on the cats.<ref name=\"Ottawa\" /> Disney saw the preliminary sketches and approved the project shortly before his death.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=266&dat=19701209&id=aucrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OWcFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1223,6636365&hl=en|last=Thomas|first=Bob|authorlink=Bob Thomas (reporter)|title='Aristocats' Has Disney Touch|newspaper=[[Kentucky New Era]]|via=Google News Archive|date=December 9, 1970|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> After ''The Jungle Book'' was completed, the animation department began work on ''Aristocats''.<ref name=\"Ottawa\" /> Hibler was eventually replaced by Reitherman,<ref name=\"mouseplanet\" /> who would abandon the more emotional story of Duchess's obsession to find adopters befitting of her kittens' talents initially favored by Disney suggesting instead the film be conceived as an adventure comedy in the vein of ''One Hundred and One Dalmatians''. Furthermore, the character Elmira, the maid, who was intended to be voiced by [[Elsa Lanchester]], was removed from the story placing Edgar as the central villain in order to better simplify the storyline.<ref name=jimhill>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Jim|title=Would Walt's version of \"The Aristocats\" have been a bigger hit for Disney Studios?|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2012/08/21/would-walt-s-version-of-quot-the-aristocats-quot-have-been-a-bigger-hit-for-disney-studios.aspx#sthash.vb0zEDZT.dpuf|publisher=Jim Hill Media|date=August 21, 2012|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nAs with ''The Jungle Book'', the characters were patterned on the personalities of the voice actors.<ref name=\"Ottawa\" /> In 1966, Walt Disney contacted [[Phil Harris]] to improvise the script, and shortly after, he was cast to voice Thomas O'Malley. To differentiate the character from [[Baloo]], Reitherman noted O'Malley was \"more based on [[Clark Gable]] than [[Wallace Beery]], who was partly the model for Baloo.\"<ref name=\"Ottawa\" /> Reitherman furthermore cast [[Eva Gabor]] as Duchess, remarking she had \"the freshest femme voice we've ever had\", and [[Sterling Holloway]] as Roquefort.<ref name=\"Ottawa\" /> [[Louis Armstrong]] was initially reported to voice Scat Cat,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2194&dat=19680803&id=JLMyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=k-wFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2175,591920&hl=en|last=Thomas|first=Bob|title=First Cartoon Minus Walt|newspaper=Ottawa Citizen|via=Google News Archive|date=August 3, 1968|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> but he backed out of the project due to illness.<ref>{{cite book|last=Johnson|first=Jimmy|title=Inside the Whimsy Works: My Life with Walt Disney Productions|publisher=[[University Press of Mississippi]]|chapter=Roy Completes Walt Disney's Dream|url=https://books.google.com/?id=yiTBAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA172&lpg=PA172&dq=jimmy+johnson+louis+armstrong+aristocats#v=onepage&q=jimmy%20johnson%20louis%20armstrong%20aristocats&f=false|pages=172\u20133|date=January 21, 2014|accessdate=June 17, 2017|isbn=9781617039300}}</ref> Out of desperation, [[Scatman Crothers]] was hired to voice the character under the direction to imitate Armstrong.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Jim|url=http://www.laughingplace.com/w/legacy/News-PID115010-115012.asp/|title=The Greatest Performances You Never Got to Hear|publisher=The Laughing Place|date=April 3, 2001|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> [[Pat Buttram]] and [[George Lindsey]] were cast as the farm dogs, which proved so popular with the filmmakers that another scene was included to have the dogs when Edgar returns to the farm to retrieve his displaced hat and umbrella.{{sfn|Koenig|1997|p=141}}\n\n===Animation===\nKen Anderson spent eighteen months developing the design of the characters.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Disney Cartoon Feature In the Works|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19671208&id=uMQtAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1p8FAAAAIBAJ&pg=6399,1742375&hl=en|newspaper=[[The Montreal Gazette]]|via=Google News Archive|date=December 8, 1967|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> Five of Disney's legendary \"[[Disney's Nine Old Men|Nine Old Men]]\" worked on it, including the Disney crew that had been working 25 years on average.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://disney.go.com/vault/archives/movies/aristocats/aristocats.html|title=\"The Aristocats\" Movie History|publisher=Disney.go.com|archivedate=January 11, 2008|accessdate=June 13, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080111034150/http://disney.go.com/vault/archives/movies/aristocats/aristocats.html}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n''The Aristocats'' was the last Disney animated feature [[Sherman Brothers|Robert and Richard Sherman]] worked on as staff songwriters, growing frustrated by the management of the studio following Walt Disney's death. For the Disney studios, the Sherman Brothers completed their work before the release of ''[[Bedknobs and Broomsticks]]'', but would return to the studio to compose songs for ''[[The Tigger Movie]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/feb/11/entertainment/ca-63175|title=The Pair Who Write Songs for Nannies and Pooh Bears|last=King|first=Susan|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 11, 2000|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Maurice_Chevalier_1968.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Maurice Chevalier (pictured here) was brought out of retirement to sing the title song.]]\n\nThe brothers composed multiple songs, but only the title song and \"Scales and Arpeggios\" were included in the film.{{sfn|Koenig|1997|p=141}} Desiring to capture the essence of France, the Sherman Brothers composed the song \"The Aristocats\". Disney film producer [[Bill Anderson (producer)|Bill Anderson]] would ask [[Maurice Chevalier]] to participate in the film.<ref>{{cite book|first=John|last=Grant|title=The Encyclopedia of Walt Disney's Animated Characters|page=274|publisher=Disney Editions|isbn=978-1562829049|date=January 1, 1993}}</ref> Following the suggestion, Richard Sherman imitated Chevalier's voice as he performed a demo for the song. Chevalier received the demo and was brought out of retirement to sing the song. Deleted songs that were intended for the film included \"Pourquoi?\" sung by [[Hermione Baddeley]] as Madame Bonfamille, its reprise, and \"She Never Felt Alone\" sung by Robie Lester as Marie.<ref name=Sherman>{{cite video|title=The Sherman Brothers: The Aristocats of Disney Songs|year=2008|publisher=Walt Disney Home Entertainment}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Rome|first=Emily|title='The Aristocats' on Blu-ray: Songwriter Richard Sherman reflects on the Disney classic and working with Walt|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2012/08/21/the-aristocats-richard-sherman-music|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=August 21, 2012|accessdate=June 10, 2016}}</ref> For the show-stopping number, the Sherman Brothers composed \"Le Jazz Hot\", but \"Ev'rybody Wants to Be a Cat\", composed by [[Floyd Huddleston]] and [[Al Rinker]], was used instead.{{sfn|Koenig|1997|pp=141\u20132}} Lastly, a villainous song was envisioned to be sung by Edgar and his assistant Elmira as a romantic duet, but the song was dropped when Elmira was removed from the story.<ref>{{cite interview|interviewer=J\u00e9r\u00e9mie Noyer|subject=Richard Sherman|title=Scales and Arpeggios: Richard M. Sherman and the \"mewsic\" of The AristoCats!|url=http://animatedviews.com/2008/richard-sherman-on-scoring-the-artistocats/|publisher=Animated Views|date=February 4, 2008|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAnother deleted song was for Thomas O'Malley titled \"My Way's The Highway\", but the filmmakers had [[Terry Gilkyson]] compose the [[eponym]]ous song \"Thomas O'Malley Cat\". Gilkyson explained \"It was the same song, but they orchestrated it twice. They used the simpler one, because they may have thought the other too elaborate or too hot. It was a jazz version with a full orchestra.\"{{sfn|Koenig|1997|p=142}}\n\nThe instrumental music was composed by [[George Bruns]], who drew from his background with jazz bands in the 1940s and decided to feature the accordion-like [[Musette de cour|musette]] for French flavor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://disney.go.com/vault/archives/movies/aristocats/aristocats.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201023829/http://disney.go.com/vault/archives/movies/aristocats/aristocats.html|title=The Aristocats|publisher=Disney.go.com|archivedate=February 1, 2011|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn ''[[Classic Disney: 60 Years of Musical Magic]]'', this includes \"Thomas O'Malley Cat\" on the [[Classic Disney: 60 Years of Musical Magic#Disc four|purple disc]] and \"Ev'rybody Wants to Be a Cat\" on the [[Classic Disney: 60 Years of Musical Magic#Disc five|orange disc]]. On ''Disney's Greatest Hits'', this includes \"Ev'rybody Wants to Be a Cat\" on the red disc.\n\nOn August 21, 2015, in honor of the 45th anniversary of the film, a [[Walt Disney Records: The Legacy Collection#The Aristocats|new soundtrack]] was released as part of ''[[Walt Disney Records: The Legacy Collection]]''.  The release includes the songs and score as used in the film, along with ''The Lost Chords of the Aristocats'' (featuring songs written for the film but not used), and previously released album versions of the songs as bonus tracks.<ref name=PRFinal4>{{cite web|title=Walt Disney Records Announce The Final Four Releases In The Walt Disney Records The Legacy Collection Series: \"Lady And The Tramp\", \"Pocahontas\", \"The Aristocats\", And \"Disneyland\"|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/walt-disney-records-announce-the-final-four-releases-in-the-walt-disney-records-the-legacy-collection-series-lady-and-the-tramp-pocahontas-the-aristocats-and-disneyland-300132012.html|publisher=PRNewswire|accessdate=August 22, 2015|location=Burbank, California|format=Press release|date=August 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''The Aristocats'' was originally released to theaters on December 24, 1970. It was re-released in theaters in 1980 and 1987.\n\n===Home media===\nIt was released on VHS in Europe on January 1, 1990 and in the UK in 1995. It was first released on VHS in North America on April 24, 1996 as part of the Masterpiece Collection.\n \nIn January 2000, Walt Disney Home Video launched the Gold Classic Collection, and ''The Aristocats'' was released on VHS and DVD on April 4, 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laughingplace.com/News-ID10001170.asp|title=Walt Disney Home Video Debuts the \"Gold Classic Collection\"|publisher=The Laughing Place|accessdate=June 10, 2016}}</ref> The DVD contained the film in its 1.33:1 [[Aspect ratio (image)|aspect ratio]] enhanced with Dolby 2.0 [[surround sound]].<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20000815083128/http://disney.go.com/disneyvideos/disneygold/aristocats.html |url=http://disney.go.com/disneyvideos/disneygold/html/aristocats.html|title=The Aristocats&nbsp;\u2014 Disney Gold Collection|archivedate=August 15, 2000|accessdate=June 10, 2016|publisher=[[Disney.com|Disney.go.com]]}}</ref> The Gold Collection release was quietly discontinued in 2006. A new single-disc Special Edition DVD (previously announced as a 2-Disc set) was released on February 5, 2008.\n\nDisney released the film on Blu-ray for the first time on August 21, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Aristocats-Two-Disc-Blu-ray-Special-Packaging/dp/B0084IHVC0/ref=sr_1_3?s=movies-tv&ie=UTF8&qid=1339106991&sr=1-3|title=The Aristocats (Two-Disc Blu-ray/DVD Special Edition in Blu-ray Packaging)|publisher=Amazon.com|accessdate=2012-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Aristocats-Two-Disc-Blu-ray-Special-Packaging/dp/B0084IHVDO/ref=sr_1_10?s=movies-tv&ie=UTF8&qid=1339107568&sr=1-10|title=The Aristocats (Two-Disc Blu-ray/DVD Special Edition in DVD Packaging)|publisher=Amazon.com|accessdate=2012-11-27}}</ref> The 2-disc Special Edition Blu-ray/DVD combo (both in Blu-ray and DVD packaging) featured a new digital transfer and new bonus material.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://disneydvd.disney.go.com/the-aristocats-special-edition.html|title=The Aristocats: Special Edition &#124; Now On Blu-ray and DVD Combo Pack|publisher=Disneydvd.disney.go.com|accessdate=2012-11-27|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121118123617/http://disneydvd.disney.go.com/the-aristocats-special-edition.html|archivedate=2012-11-18}}</ref> A single disc DVD edition was also released on the same day.<ref>{{cite web|author=The Aristocats (Special Edition)|url=https://www.amazon.com/Aristocats-Special-Edition-Phil-Harris/dp/B0084IHVGG/ref=sr_1_20?s=movies-tv&ie=UTF8&qid=1339107655&sr=1-20|title=The Aristocats (Special Edition)|publisher=Amazon.com|accessdate=2012-11-27}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''The Aristocats'' was released in December 1970 where it earned $10.1 million in United States and Canadian rentals by the end of 1971.<ref>{{cite news|title='Love Story' named year's top money-maker|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1298&dat=19720117&id=39tNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5YoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4216,1574122&hl=en|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[Free Lance-Star]]|date=January 17, 1972|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> The film was the most popular \"general release\" movie at the British box office in 1971.<ref>''The Times'' [London, England] December 30, 1971: p. 2; ''The Times Digital Archive''; accessed July 11, 2012.</ref> The film was the most popular film in France in 1971 and had total admissions of 12.7 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficestory.com/france-1971-c22928631|title=Box Office Annuel France 1971 Top 10 |date=July 17, 2016|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> It is also ranked as the eighteenth highest-grossing of all time in France.<ref name=\"FranceAdm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/top100.php?view=2|title=Top250 Tous Les Temps En France (reprises incluses) |accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref> The film is the most popular film released in Germany in 1971 with admissions of 11.3 million being the country's eleventh highest-grossing film.<ref name=\"GermanAdm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.insidekino.com/DJahr/DAlltime100.htm|title=Top 100 Deutschland |publisher=Insider Kino|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref> By the end of its initial theatrical run, the film had earned domestic rentals of $11 million and $17 million in foreign countries,<ref>{{cite news|last=Philips|first=McCandlish|author-link=McCandlish Phillips|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/07/18/archives/disney-empire-is-hardly-mickey-mouse-classic-advancement-song.html|title=Disney Empire is Hardly Mickey Mouse|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 18, 1973|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Disney's Dandy Detailed Data; 'Robin Hood' Takes $27,500,000; Films Corporate Gravy-Maker|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 15, 1975|page=3}}</ref> for a worldwide rental of $28 million.\n\nThe film was re-released to theaters in the United States on December 19, 1980 where it grossed an additional $18 million and again on April 10, 1987 where it grossed $17 million.<ref>{{cite web|last=Seigel|first=Robert|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=9352|title=The Making of Walt Disney's The Aristocats|website=blu-ray.com|date=August 25, 2012|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> The film grossed $32 million worldwide from an international re-release in 1994.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Daily Variety]]|page=17|date=April 19, 1995|last=Groves|first=Don|title=O'seas Mines Big B.O.}}</ref> ''The Aristocats'' has had a lifetime gross of $55.7 million in the United States and Canada,<ref name=numbers>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1970/0ARIS.php|publisher=The Numbers|title=The Aristocats, Box Office Information|accessdate=January 10, 2012}}</ref> and its total lifetime worldwide box office gross is $191 million.<ref name=\"DisneyWW\"/>\n\n===Critical reaction===\n[[Howard Thompson (film critic)|Howard Thompson]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised the film as \"grand fun all the way, nicely flavored with tunes, and topped with one of the funniest jam sessions ever by a bunch of scraggly Bohemians headed by one Scat Cat.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Thompson|first=Howard|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/12/26/archives/the-aristocats-warm-animated-cartoon-by-disney-opens.html|title='The Aristocats,' Warm Animated cartoon by Disney, Opens|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 26, 1970|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]], writing for the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', awarded the film three stars out of four summarizing ''The Aristocats'' as \"light and pleasant and funny, the characterization is strong, and the voices of Phil Harris (O'Malley the Alley Cat) and Eva Gabor (Duchess, the mother cat) are charming in their absolute rightness.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Ebert|first=Roger|authorlink=Roger Ebert|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-aristocats-1971|title=The Aristocats Movie Review|work=rogerebert.com|date=January 1, 1971|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> [[Charles Champlin]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote that the film \"has a gentle good-natured charm which will delight the small-fry and their elders alike.\" He praised the animation, but remarked that the film \"lacks a certain kind of vigor, boldness and dash, a kind of a hard-focused emphasis which you would say was a Disney trademark.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Champlin|first=Charles|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/384821255/|title=Cats Star in Disney Cartoon|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|page=Section II, pgs. 4, 11|url-access=subscription|via=Newspapers.com|date=December 24, 1970|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised the film writing the film is \"[h]elped immeasurably by the voices of Phil Harris, Eva Gabor, Sterling Holloway, Scatman Crothers and others, plus some outstanding animation, songs, sentiment, some excellent dialog and even a touch of psychedelia.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/1969/film/reviews/the-aristocats-1200422129/|title=Movie Review: The Aristocats|work=Variety|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref> [[Stefan Kanfer]], reviewing for ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', noted that \"The melodies in Disney's earlier efforts have been richer. But for integration of music, comedy and plot, ''The Aristocats'' has no rivals.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Kanter|first=Stefan|title=Cinema: Top Bubble|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221210827/https://time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,904670,00.html|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,904670,00.html|magazine=Time|volume=97|issue=4|archivedate=December 21, 2008|date=January 25, 1971|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref> \n\nFor its 1987 re-release, animation historian Charles Solomon expressed criticism for its episodic plot, anachronisms, and borrowed plot elements from earlier Disney animated features, but nevertheless wrote \"[b]ut even at their least original, the Disney artists provide better animation--and more entertainment--than the recent animated features hawking ''[[The Care Bears Movie|The Care Bears]]'', ''[[Rainbow Brite and the Star Stealer|Rainbow Brite]]'' and ''[[The Transformers: The Movie|Transformers]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Solomon|first=Charles|title=Movie Review: 'The Aristocats': Walt Left A Gap|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-04-09/entertainment/ca-176_1_walt-disney|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=April 9, 1987|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> Writing in his book ''The Disney Films'', Disney historian and film critic [[Leonard Maltin]] wrote that \"[t]he worst that one could say of ''The AristoCats'' is that it is unmemorable. It's smoothly executed, of course, and enjoyable, but neither its superficial story nor its characters have any resonance.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Maltin|first=Leonard|authorlink=Leonard Maltin|title=The Disney Films|publisher=Disney Editions|page=262|isbn=978-0786885275|date=August 28, 2000}}</ref> Additionally, in his book ''Of Mice and Magic'', Maltin criticized the film for re-using Phil Harris to replicate ''The Jungle Book''{{'}}s Baloo, dismissing the character Thomas O'Malley as \"essentially the same character, dictated by the same voice personality.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Maltin|first=Leonard|title=Of Mice and Magic: A History of American Animated Cartoons, Revised and Updated Edition|publisher=[[Plume (publisher)|Plume]]|isbn=978-0452259935|date=December 1, 1987|page=76}}</ref> \n\nThe [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that the film received a 66% approval rating with an average rating of 5.9/10 based on 32 reviews. Its consensus states \"Though ''The Aristocats'' is a mostly middling effort for Disney, it is redeemed by terrific work from its voice cast and some jazzy tunes.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/aristocats|title=The Aristocats|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|work=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=September 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nThe film is recognized by [[American Film Institute]] in these lists:\n* 2008: [[AFI's 10 Top 10]]:\n** Nominated Animation Film<ref>{{cite web|url=http://connect.afi.com/site/DocServer/10top10.pdf?docID=381&AddInterest=1781 |title=AFI's 10 Top 10 Nominees |format=PDF |accessdate=2016-08-19 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716071937/http://connect.afi.com/site/DocServer/10top10.pdf?docID=381&AddInterest=1781 |archivedate=2011-07-16 }}</ref>\n\n==Canceled sequel==\nIn 2005, [[DisneyToon Studios]] originally planned to make a follow-up to the film, along with sequels to ''[[Chicken Little (2005 film)|Chicken Little]]'' (2005) and ''[[Meet the Robinsons]]'' (2007).<ref name=\"sequel\">{{cite web|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2007/06/21/say-so-long-to-direct-to-video-sequels-disneytoon-studios-tunes-out-sharon-morrill.aspx|title=Say \"So Long !\" to direct-to-video sequels : DisneyToon Studios tunes out Sharon Morrill|last=Hill|first=Jim|publisher=Jim Hill Media|date=June 20, 2007|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Originally intended to be a 2D animated feature, Disney executives decided to produce the film in [[computer animation]] in order to garner more interest.<ref>{{cite web|last=Noyer|first=J\u00e9r\u00e9mie|url=http://animatedviews.com/2008/disneytoon-studios-and-the-sequels-that-never-were-with-tod-carter/|title=DisneyToon Studios and The Sequels That Never Were, with Tod Carter|publisher=Animated Views|date=October 20, 2008|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Additionally, the story was meant to center around Marie, Duchess's daughter, who becomes smitten by another kitten aboard a luxury cruise ship. However, she and her family must soon take on a jewel thief on the open seas.<ref>{{cite news|last=Armstrong|first=Josh|url=http://animatedviews.com/2013/from-snow-queen-to-pinocchio-ii-robert-reeces-animated-adventures-in-screenwriting/|title=From ''Snow Queen'' to ''Pinocchio II'': Robert Reece's animated adventures in screenwriting|publisher=Animated Views|date=April 22, 2013|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref> The project was canceled when [[John Lasseter]] was named Disney's new chief creative officer, in which he called off all future sequels DisneyToon had planned and instead make original productions or spin-offs.<ref name=\"sequel\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of highest-grossing animated films]]\n* [[List of highest-grossing films in France]]\n* [[List of American films of 1970]]\n* [[List of animated feature films of 1970]]\n* [[List of Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n* [[List of Disney theatrical animated features]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last=Koenig|first=David|title=Mouse Under Glass: Secrets of Disney Animation & Theme Parks|location=[[Irvine, California]]|publisher=Bonaventure Press|isbn=978-0964060517|year=1997|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|0065421}}\n* {{tcmdb title|67588|The Aristocats}}\n* {{bcdb title|3}}\n* [http://www.toonopedia.com/arstocat.htm ''The Aristocats''] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/66gYYN0Ss?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/arstocat.htm Archived] from the original on April 4, 2012.\n\n{{Sherman Brothers}}\n{{Wolfgang Reitherman}}\n{{Disney theatrical animated features}}\n{{Walt Disney Animation Studios}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aristocats, The}}\n[[Category:1970 animated films]]\n[[Category:1970 films]]\n[[Category:1970s American animated films]]\n[[Category:1970s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:1970s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure films]]\n[[Category:American musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about cats]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about families]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Wolfgang Reitherman]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1910]]\n[[Category:Films set in France]]\n[[Category:Films set in Paris]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Animation Studios films]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n[[Category:1970s children's animated films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1970 American animated film produced by Walt Disney Productions}}\n{{distinguish|The Aristocrats}}\n{{pp-semi-protected|small=yes}}\n{{Expand French|Les Aristochats|date=April 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name        = The Aristocats\n| image       = aristoposter.jpg\n| caption     = Original theatrical release poster\n| director    = [[Wolfgang Reitherman]]\n| producer    = [[Winston Hibler]]<br/>Wolfgang Reitherman\n| story       = [[Ken Anderson (animator)|Ken Anderson]]<br/>Larry Clemmons<br/>Eric Cleworth<br/>Vance Gerry<br/>Julius Svendsen<br/>[[Frank Thomas (animator)|Frank Thomas]]<br/>[[Ralph Wright]]\n| based on    = \"The Aristocats\" by Tom McGowan and Tom Rowe \n| studio      = [[Walt Disney Animation Studios|Walt Disney Productions]]\n| distributor = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Distribution]]\n| music       = [[George Bruns]]\n| starring    = [[Phil Harris]]<br/>[[Eva Gabor]]<br/>[[Hermione Baddeley]]<br/>[[Gary Dubin]]<br/>[[#Cast|Dean Clark]]<br/>[[Sterling Holloway]]<br/>[[Roddy Maude-Roxby]]<br/>[[Louise English|Liz English]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1970|12|11|premiere|1970|12|24|United States}} <!-- First and Country of Origin releases per WP:FILMRELEASE. -->\n| runtime     = 79 minutes\n| country     = United States\n| language    = English\n| budget      = $4 million<ref>{{cite news|last=Scott|first=Vernon|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/42762710/the_logansport_press/|title=News from Hollywood|newspaper=[[Pharos-Tribune|The Logansport Press]]|page=6|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|date=February 17, 1971|accessdate=January 21, 2020}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n| gross       = $191 million<ref name=\"DisneyWW\">{{cite magazine|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|title=Cartoon Coffers - Top-Grossing Disney Animated Features at the Worldwide B.O.|date=October 27, 2003|page=6}}</ref>}}\n\n'''''The Aristocats''''' is a 1970 American animated [[Romance film|romantic]] [[Adventure film|adventure]] [[Musical film|musical]] [[Comedy film|comedy]] film directed by [[Wolfgang Reitherman]]. It was produced by [[Walt Disney Productions]] and released by [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Buena Vista Distribution]]. The 20th [[List of Walt Disney Animation Studios films|Disney animated feature film]], the film is based on a story by Tom McGowan and Tom Rowe, and revolves around a family of [[Aristocracy (class)|aristocrat]]ic cats, and how an alley cat acquaintance helps them after a [[butler]] has kidnapped them to gain his mistress's fortune which was intended to go to them. The film features the voices of [[Eva Gabor]], [[Hermione Baddeley]], [[Phil Harris]], Dean Clark, [[Sterling Holloway]], [[Scatman Crothers]], and [[Roddy Maude-Roxby]].\n\nIn 1962, ''The Aristocats'' project began as an original script for a two-part live-action episode for ''[[Walt Disney anthology television series#Walt Disney.27s Wonderful World of Color .281961.E2.80.931969.29|Walt Disney's Wonderful World of Color]]'', developed by writers Tom McGowan and Tom Rowe and producer Harry Tytle. Following two years of re-writes, [[Walt Disney]] suggested the project would be more suitable for an animated film, and placed the project in [[Turnaround (filmmaking)|turnaround]] as ''[[The Jungle Book (1967 film)|The Jungle Book]]'' advanced into production. When ''The Jungle Book'' was nearly complete, Disney appointed [[Ken Anderson (animator)|Ken Anderson]] to develop preliminary work on ''The Aristocats'', making it the last film project to be approved by Disney personally before his death in December 1966.\n\n''The Aristocats'' was released on December 24, 1970 to positive reception and was a box office success.\n\n==Plot==\n<!--Per WP:FILMPLOT, plot length should be between 400 and 700 words. Current count is 483 words.-->\n\nIn [[Paris, France|Paris]] 1910, mother cat Duchess and her three [[kitten]]s, Berlioz, Marie, and Toulouse, live with retired opera diva Madame Adelaide Bonfamille, and her English butler, Edgar. One day while preparing her [[will (law)|will]] with lawyer Georges Hautecourt, Madame declares her fortune to be left to her cats until their deaths, and thereafter to Edgar. Edgar hears this through a [[speaking tube]] and plots to eliminate the cats. Therefore, he sedates the cats by putting [[sleeping pills]] in a milk mixture intended for them, and enters the countryside to abandon them. There, he is ambushed by two [[hound]]s named Napoleon and Lafayette, and the cats are stranded in the countryside, while Madame Adelaide, Roquefort the mouse and Frou-Frou the horse discover their absence.\n\nIn the morning, Duchess meets an alley cat named Thomas O'Malley, who offers to guide her and the kittens to Paris. The group briefly [[hitchhiking|hitchhikes]] in a milk truck before being chased off by the driver. Later, while crossing a railroad trestle, the cats narrowly avoid an oncoming train, but Marie falls into a river and is saved by O'Malley, who in turn has to be rescued himself by two English geese, Amelia and Abigail Gabble, who accompany the cats to Paris. Edgar returns to the country to retrieve his possessions from Napoleon and Lafayette, as the only evidence that could incriminate him.\n\nTravelling across the rooftops of the city, the cats meet O'Malley's friend Scat Cat and his musicians, who perform the song \"Ev'rybody Wants to Be a Cat\". After the band has departed, O'Malley and Duchess converse on a nearby rooftop while the kittens listen at a windowsill. Here, Duchess' loyalty to Madame prompts her to decline O'Malley's proposal of marriage. Duchess and the kittens return to Madame's mansion, but Edgar places them in a sack and prepares to ship them to [[Timbuktu]]; They direct Roquefort to retrieve O'Malley. He does so, and O'Malley returns to the mansion, instructing Roquefort to find Scat Cat and his gang. The alley cats and Frou-Frou fight Edgar, while Roquefort frees Duchess and the kittens. At the end of the fight, Edgar is locked in his own packing-case and sent to Timbuktu himself, never to be seen again. Madame Adelaide's will is rewritten to exclude Edgar, with Madame remaining ignorant of the reason for Edgar's departure. After adopting O\u2019Malley into the family, Madame establishes a charity foundation housing Paris' stray cats (represented by Scat Cat and his band, who reprise their song).\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Eva Gabor]] as Duchess \u2013 Madame Adelaide's cat and mother of three kittens, forced to choose between loyalty to Madame and her own attachment to Thomas O'Malley at the end of the film. [[Robie Lester]] provided the singing voice for Duchess.\n* [[Phil Harris]] as Thomas O'Malley (full name: Abraham de Lacy Giuseppe Casey Thomas O'Malley) \u2013 A feral cat who befriends Duchess and her kittens, becoming a father figure to the kittens and falling in love with Duchess. For cultural reasons, the [[Italian language|Italian]] dubbing of the film changes him to \u201cRomeo, er mejo der Colosseo\u201d ([[Roman dialect]] for \"The best [cat] of the [[Colosseum]]\"), an Italian cat from [[Rome]] speaking with a strong Roman accent. O'Malley is a cat from Rome in the Italian dub because In Italy, it was widely known that until recent times there were lots of Alley Cats in the Colosseum.\n* [[Gary Dubin]] as Toulouse \u2013 the oldest kitten, who idolizes all alley cats and especially Thomas. He is also a talented painter and is loosely based on French painter [[Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec]].\n* [[Louise English|Liz English]] as Marie \u2013 middle kitten; often imperious or snobbish to her brothers, but her mother's special companion. Something of a singer.\n* Dean Clark as Berlioz \u2013 the youngest kitten. He is somewhat timid and shy, named after the French composer [[Hector Berlioz]]. This Berlioz is a talented pianist.\n* [[Roddy Maude-Roxby]] as Edgar Balthazar \u2013 Madame Adelaide's dim-witted butler who tries to get rid of the cats in order to inherit her fortune.\n* [[Scatman Crothers]] as Scat Cat \u2013 Thomas' best friend and leader of a gang of [[jazz]]-playing alley cats. Scat Cat plays the trumpet.\n* [[Paul Winchell]] as Shun Gon \u2013 a Chinese cat in Scat Cat's gang. Plays the piano and drums that are made out of pots.\n* [[Lord Tim Hudson]] as Hit Cat \u2013 an English cat in Scat Cat's gang. Plays acoustic guitar.\n* [[Vito Scotti]] as Peppo \u2013 an Italian cat in Scat Cat's gang. Plays the accordion.\n* [[Thurl Ravenscroft]] as Billy Boss \u2013 a Russian cat in Scat Cat's gang. Plays the double bass.\n* [[Sterling Holloway]] as Roquefort \u2013 A house mouse and also a friend of the cats, who assists in the expulsion of Edgar.\n* [[Pat Buttram]] as Napoleon \u2013 a [[Bloodhound]] who attacks Edgar when he intrudes in the farm where Napoleon lives. Napoleon insists, whenever cohort Lafayette makes a suggestion, that he is in command, then adopts Lafayette's suggestion as his own.\n* [[George Lindsey]] as Lafayette \u2013 a [[Basset Hound]] and Napoleon's companion. He sometimes proves smarter than Napoleon, but is also more timid.\n* [[Hermione Baddeley]] as Madame Adelaide Bonfamille \u2013 a former opera singer and owner of Duchess and her kittens.\n* [[Charles Lane (actor)|Charles Lane]] as Georges Hautecourt \u2013 Madame Bonfamille's lawyer: an eccentric, lively old man\n* [[Nancy Kulp]] as Frou-Frou \u2013 Roquefort's horse companion, who subdues Edgar. [[Ruth Buzzi]] provided her singing voice.\n* [[Monica Evans]] as Abigail Gabble \u2013 a goose who befriends the cats.\n* [[Carole Shelley]] as Amelia Gabble \u2013 Abigail's twin sister.\n* [[Bill Thompson (voice actor)|Bill Thompson]] as Uncle Waldo \u2013 the drunken gander uncle of Abigail and Amelia.\n* [[Peter Renaday]] as French Milkman/Le Petit Cafe Cook/Truck Movers (uncredited)\n\n==Production==\n\n===Story development===\nOn December 9, 1961, Walt Disney suggested that Harry Tytle and Tom McGowan find some animal stories to adapt as a two-part live-action episode for the ''[[Walt Disney anthology television series#Walt Disney.27s Wonderful World of Color .281961.E2.80.931969.29|Wonderful World of Color]]'' television program. By New Year's 1962, McGowan had found several stories including a children's book about a mother cat and her kittens set in New York City. However, Tytle felt that a [[London]] location had added a significant element to ''[[One Hundred and One Dalmatians]]'' and suggested setting the story of the cats in Paris.<ref name=\"mouseplanet\">{{cite web|last=Sampson|first=Wade|title=The Secret Origin of the Aristocats|url=https://www.mouseplanet.com/9084/The_Secret_Origin_of_the_Aristocats|publisher=Mouse Planet|date=December 23, 2009|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> Following a rough storyline, the story became about two servants\u2014a butler and a maid\u2014who were in line to inherit a fortune of an eccentric mistress after the pet cats died and focused on their feeble and foolish attempts to eliminate the felines. [[Boris Karloff]] and [[Francoise Rosay]] were in mind to portray the butler and the distressed Madame.{{sfn|Koenig|1997|p=141}} A subplot centered around a mother cat hiding her kittens to keep them out of danger in a variety of different homes and locales around Paris, France. During the filming of ''[[Escapade in Florence]]'', McGowan brought him the story that had been written by Tom Rowe, an American writer who was living in Paris.<ref name=\"mouseplanet\" />\n\n[[File:Phil Harris 1956.JPG|thumb|right|150px|Before his death in 1966, Walt Disney contacted Phil Harris (pictured here) to voice Thomas O'Malley.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=336&dat=19801208&id=SfVSAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ToMDAAAAIBAJ&pg=7155,2696962&hl=en||title=An encore purr-formance for 'The Aristocats'|last=Pearson|first=Howard|newspaper=[[Deseret News]]|via=[[Google News Archive]]|date=December 8, 1980|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref>]]\n\nBy August 1962, they sent the completed script to Burbank, where it was returned as \"rejected\" by an unknown executive at the Disney studios. Nevertheless, Tytle brought the script to Disney staying at the [[Connaught Hall, London|Connaught]] in London. Disney approved for the draft, but recommended additional cuts which were made by February 1963. Before filming was to commence, Rowe wrote a letter to Disney addressing his displeasure of the script revisions, in which Tytle responded to Rowe that the changes Disney approved of would be kept. However, by summer 1963, the project was shelved, where Tytle, in a discussion with Walt, recommended to produce ''The Aristocats'' as an animated feature.<ref name=\"mouseplanet\" /> For that reason, Disney temporarily shelved the project as the animation department was occupied with ''[[The Jungle Book (1967 film)|The Jungle Book]]''.<ref name=\"Ottawa\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2194&dat=19701218&id=kr0yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XO0FAAAAIBAJ&pg=2560,1843732&hl=en|title=The Aristocats for Christmas|newspaper=[[Ottawa Citizen]]|via=Google News Archive|date=December 18, 1970|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> Meanwhile, director [[Wolfgang Reitherman]] learned of the project and suggested it as a follow-up project to ''Jungle Book''.<ref name=jimhill /> Because of the production delays, Tytle was advised to centralize his efforts on [[Live action|live action projects]] and was replaced by [[Winston Hibler]].<ref name=\"mouseplanet\" />\n\nIn 1966, Disney assigned [[Ken Anderson (animator)|Ken Anderson]] to determine whether ''Aristocats'' would be suitable for an animated feature. With occasional guidance from Reitherman, Anderson worked from scratch and simplified the two stories into a story that focused more on the cats.<ref name=\"Ottawa\" /> Disney saw the preliminary sketches and approved the project shortly before his death.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=266&dat=19701209&id=aucrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OWcFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1223,6636365&hl=en|last=Thomas|first=Bob|authorlink=Bob Thomas (reporter)|title='Aristocats' Has Disney Touch|newspaper=[[Kentucky New Era]]|via=Google News Archive|date=December 9, 1970|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> After ''The Jungle Book'' was completed, the animation department began work on ''Aristocats''.<ref name=\"Ottawa\" /> Hibler was eventually replaced by Reitherman,<ref name=\"mouseplanet\" /> who would abandon the more emotional story of Duchess's obsession to find adopters befitting of her kittens' talents initially favored by Disney suggesting instead the film be conceived as an adventure comedy in the vein of ''One Hundred and One Dalmatians''. Furthermore, the character Elmira, the maid, who was intended to be voiced by [[Elsa Lanchester]], was removed from the story placing Edgar as the central villain in order to better simplify the storyline.<ref name=jimhill>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Jim|title=Would Walt's version of \"The Aristocats\" have been a bigger hit for Disney Studios?|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2012/08/21/would-walt-s-version-of-quot-the-aristocats-quot-have-been-a-bigger-hit-for-disney-studios.aspx#sthash.vb0zEDZT.dpuf|publisher=Jim Hill Media|date=August 21, 2012|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nAs with ''The Jungle Book'', the characters were patterned on the personalities of the voice actors.<ref name=\"Ottawa\" /> In 1966, Walt Disney contacted [[Phil Harris]] to improvise the script, and shortly after, he was cast to voice Thomas O'Malley. To differentiate the character from [[Baloo]], Reitherman noted O'Malley was \"more based on [[Clark Gable]] than [[Wallace Beery]], who was partly the model for Baloo.\"<ref name=\"Ottawa\" /> Reitherman furthermore cast [[Eva Gabor]] as Duchess, remarking she had \"the freshest femme voice we've ever had\", and [[Sterling Holloway]] as Roquefort.<ref name=\"Ottawa\" /> [[Louis Armstrong]] was initially reported to voice Scat Cat,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2194&dat=19680803&id=JLMyAAAAIBAJ&sjid=k-wFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2175,591920&hl=en|last=Thomas|first=Bob|title=First Cartoon Minus Walt|newspaper=Ottawa Citizen|via=Google News Archive|date=August 3, 1968|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> but he backed out of the project due to illness.<ref>{{cite book|last=Johnson|first=Jimmy|title=Inside the Whimsy Works: My Life with Walt Disney Productions|publisher=[[University Press of Mississippi]]|chapter=Roy Completes Walt Disney's Dream|url=https://books.google.com/?id=yiTBAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA172&lpg=PA172&dq=jimmy+johnson+louis+armstrong+aristocats#v=onepage&q=jimmy%20johnson%20louis%20armstrong%20aristocats&f=false|pages=172\u20133|date=January 21, 2014|accessdate=June 17, 2017|isbn=9781617039300}}</ref> Out of desperation, [[Scatman Crothers]] was hired to voice the character under the direction to imitate Armstrong.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hill|first=Jim|url=http://www.laughingplace.com/w/legacy/News-PID115010-115012.asp/|title=The Greatest Performances You Never Got to Hear|publisher=The Laughing Place|date=April 3, 2001|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> [[Pat Buttram]] and [[George Lindsey]] were cast as the farm dogs, which proved so popular with the filmmakers that another scene was included to have the dogs when Edgar returns to the farm to retrieve his displaced hat and umbrella.{{sfn|Koenig|1997|p=141}}\n\n===Animation===\nKen Anderson spent eighteen months developing the design of the characters.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Disney Cartoon Feature In the Works|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19671208&id=uMQtAAAAIBAJ&sjid=1p8FAAAAIBAJ&pg=6399,1742375&hl=en|newspaper=[[The Montreal Gazette]]|via=Google News Archive|date=December 8, 1967|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> Five of Disney's legendary \"[[Disney's Nine Old Men|Nine Old Men]]\" worked on it, including the Disney crew that had been working 25 years on average.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://disney.go.com/vault/archives/movies/aristocats/aristocats.html|title=\"The Aristocats\" Movie History|publisher=Disney.go.com|archivedate=January 11, 2008|accessdate=June 13, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080111034150/http://disney.go.com/vault/archives/movies/aristocats/aristocats.html}}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n''The Aristocats'' was the last Disney animated feature [[Sherman Brothers|Robert and Richard Sherman]] worked on as staff songwriters, growing frustrated by the management of the studio following Walt Disney's death. For the Disney studios, the Sherman Brothers completed their work before the release of ''[[Bedknobs and Broomsticks]]'', but would return to the studio to compose songs for ''[[The Tigger Movie]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/feb/11/entertainment/ca-63175|title=The Pair Who Write Songs for Nannies and Pooh Bears|last=King|first=Susan|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 11, 2000|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Maurice_Chevalier_1968.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Maurice Chevalier (pictured here) was brought out of retirement to sing the title song.]]\n\nThe brothers composed multiple songs, but only the title song and \"Scales and Arpeggios\" were included in the film.{{sfn|Koenig|1997|p=141}} Desiring to capture the essence of France, the Sherman Brothers composed the song \"The Aristocats\". Disney film producer [[Bill Anderson (producer)|Bill Anderson]] would ask [[Maurice Chevalier]] to participate in the film.<ref>{{cite book|first=John|last=Grant|title=The Encyclopedia of Walt Disney's Animated Characters|page=274|publisher=Disney Editions|isbn=978-1562829049|date=January 1, 1993}}</ref> Following the suggestion, Richard Sherman imitated Chevalier's voice as he performed a demo for the song. Chevalier received the demo and was brought out of retirement to sing the song. Deleted songs that were intended for the film included \"Pourquoi?\" sung by [[Hermione Baddeley]] as Madame Bonfamille, its reprise, and \"She Never Felt Alone\" sung by Robie Lester as Marie.<ref name=Sherman>{{cite video|title=The Sherman Brothers: The Aristocats of Disney Songs|year=2008|publisher=Walt Disney Home Entertainment}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Rome|first=Emily|title='The Aristocats' on Blu-ray: Songwriter Richard Sherman reflects on the Disney classic and working with Walt|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2012/08/21/the-aristocats-richard-sherman-music|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=August 21, 2012|accessdate=June 10, 2016}}</ref> For the show-stopping number, the Sherman Brothers composed \"Le Jazz Hot\", but \"Ev'rybody Wants to Be a Cat\", composed by [[Floyd Huddleston]] and [[Al Rinker]], was used instead.{{sfn|Koenig|1997|pp=141\u20132}} Lastly, a villainous song was envisioned to be sung by Edgar and his assistant Elmira as a romantic duet, but the song was dropped when Elmira was removed from the story.<ref>{{cite interview|interviewer=J\u00e9r\u00e9mie Noyer|subject=Richard Sherman|title=Scales and Arpeggios: Richard M. Sherman and the \"mewsic\" of The AristoCats!|url=http://animatedviews.com/2008/richard-sherman-on-scoring-the-artistocats/|publisher=Animated Views|date=February 4, 2008|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAnother deleted song was for Thomas O'Malley titled \"My Way's The Highway\", but the filmmakers had [[Terry Gilkyson]] compose the [[eponym]]ous song \"Thomas O'Malley Cat\". Gilkyson explained \"It was the same song, but they orchestrated it twice. They used the simpler one, because they may have thought the other too elaborate or too hot. It was a jazz version with a full orchestra.\"{{sfn|Koenig|1997|p=142}}\n\nThe instrumental music was composed by [[George Bruns]], who drew from his background with jazz bands in the 1940s and decided to feature the accordion-like [[Musette de cour|musette]] for French flavor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://disney.go.com/vault/archives/movies/aristocats/aristocats.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110201023829/http://disney.go.com/vault/archives/movies/aristocats/aristocats.html|title=The Aristocats|publisher=Disney.go.com|archivedate=February 1, 2011|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn ''[[Classic Disney: 60 Years of Musical Magic]]'', this includes \"Thomas O'Malley Cat\" on the [[Classic Disney: 60 Years of Musical Magic#Disc four|purple disc]] and \"Ev'rybody Wants to Be a Cat\" on the [[Classic Disney: 60 Years of Musical Magic#Disc five|orange disc]]. On ''Disney's Greatest Hits'', this includes \"Ev'rybody Wants to Be a Cat\" on the red disc.\n\nOn August 21, 2015, in honor of the 45th anniversary of the film, a [[Walt Disney Records: The Legacy Collection#The Aristocats|new soundtrack]] was released as part of ''[[Walt Disney Records: The Legacy Collection]]''.  The release includes the songs and score as used in the film, along with ''The Lost Chords of the Aristocats'' (featuring songs written for the film but not used), and previously released album versions of the songs as bonus tracks.<ref name=PRFinal4>{{cite web|title=Walt Disney Records Announce The Final Four Releases In The Walt Disney Records The Legacy Collection Series: \"Lady And The Tramp\", \"Pocahontas\", \"The Aristocats\", And \"Disneyland\"|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/walt-disney-records-announce-the-final-four-releases-in-the-walt-disney-records-the-legacy-collection-series-lady-and-the-tramp-pocahontas-the-aristocats-and-disneyland-300132012.html|publisher=PRNewswire|accessdate=August 22, 2015|location=Burbank, California|format=Press release|date=August 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''The Aristocats'' was originally released to theaters on December 24, 1970. It was re-released in theaters in 1980 and 1987.\n\n===Home media===\nIt was released on VHS in Europe on January 1, 1990 and in the UK in 1995. It was first released on VHS in North America on April 24, 1996 as part of the Masterpiece Collection.\n \nIn January 2000, Walt Disney Home Video launched the Gold Classic Collection, and ''The Aristocats'' was released on VHS and DVD on April 4, 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laughingplace.com/News-ID10001170.asp|title=Walt Disney Home Video Debuts the \"Gold Classic Collection\"|publisher=The Laughing Place|accessdate=June 10, 2016}}</ref> The DVD contained the film in its 1.33:1 [[Aspect ratio (image)|aspect ratio]] enhanced with Dolby 2.0 [[surround sound]].<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20000815083128/http://disney.go.com/disneyvideos/disneygold/aristocats.html |url=http://disney.go.com/disneyvideos/disneygold/html/aristocats.html|title=The Aristocats&nbsp;\u2014 Disney Gold Collection|archivedate=August 15, 2000|accessdate=June 10, 2016|publisher=[[Disney.com|Disney.go.com]]}}</ref> The Gold Collection release was quietly discontinued in 2006. A new single-disc Special Edition DVD (previously announced as a 2-Disc set) was released on February 5, 2008.\n\nDisney released the film on Blu-ray for the first time on August 21, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Aristocats-Two-Disc-Blu-ray-Special-Packaging/dp/B0084IHVC0/ref=sr_1_3?s=movies-tv&ie=UTF8&qid=1339106991&sr=1-3|title=The Aristocats (Two-Disc Blu-ray/DVD Special Edition in Blu-ray Packaging)|publisher=Amazon.com|accessdate=2012-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Aristocats-Two-Disc-Blu-ray-Special-Packaging/dp/B0084IHVDO/ref=sr_1_10?s=movies-tv&ie=UTF8&qid=1339107568&sr=1-10|title=The Aristocats (Two-Disc Blu-ray/DVD Special Edition in DVD Packaging)|publisher=Amazon.com|accessdate=2012-11-27}}</ref> The 2-disc Special Edition Blu-ray/DVD combo (both in Blu-ray and DVD packaging) featured a new digital transfer and new bonus material.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://disneydvd.disney.go.com/the-aristocats-special-edition.html|title=The Aristocats: Special Edition &#124; Now On Blu-ray and DVD Combo Pack|publisher=Disneydvd.disney.go.com|accessdate=2012-11-27|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121118123617/http://disneydvd.disney.go.com/the-aristocats-special-edition.html|archivedate=2012-11-18}}</ref> A single disc DVD edition was also released on the same day.<ref>{{cite web|author=The Aristocats (Special Edition)|url=https://www.amazon.com/Aristocats-Special-Edition-Phil-Harris/dp/B0084IHVGG/ref=sr_1_20?s=movies-tv&ie=UTF8&qid=1339107655&sr=1-20|title=The Aristocats (Special Edition)|publisher=Amazon.com|accessdate=2012-11-27}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''The Aristocats'' was released in December 1970 where it earned $10.1 million in United States and Canadian rentals by the end of 1971.<ref>{{cite news|title='Love Story' named year's top money-maker|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1298&dat=19720117&id=39tNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5YoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4216,1574122&hl=en|work=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[Free Lance-Star]]|date=January 17, 1972|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> The film was the most popular \"general release\" movie at the British box office in 1971.<ref>''The Times'' [London, England] December 30, 1971: p. 2; ''The Times Digital Archive''; accessed July 11, 2012.</ref> The film was the most popular film in France in 1971 and had total admissions of 12.7 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficestory.com/france-1971-c22928631|title=Box Office Annuel France 1971 Top 10 |date=July 17, 2016|accessdate=March 14, 2018}}</ref> It is also ranked as the eighteenth highest-grossing of all time in France.<ref name=\"FranceAdm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jpbox-office.com/top100.php?view=2|title=Top250 Tous Les Temps En France (reprises incluses) |accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref> The film is the most popular film released in Germany in 1971 with admissions of 11.3 million being the country's eleventh highest-grossing film.<ref name=\"GermanAdm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.insidekino.com/DJahr/DAlltime100.htm|title=Top 100 Deutschland |publisher=Insider Kino|accessdate=March 15, 2018}}</ref> By the end of its initial theatrical run, the film had earned domestic rentals of $11 million and $17 million in foreign countries,<ref>{{cite news|last=Philips|first=McCandlish|author-link=McCandlish Phillips|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1973/07/18/archives/disney-empire-is-hardly-mickey-mouse-classic-advancement-song.html|title=Disney Empire is Hardly Mickey Mouse|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 18, 1973|accessdate=April 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=Disney's Dandy Detailed Data; 'Robin Hood' Takes $27,500,000; Films Corporate Gravy-Maker|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=January 15, 1975|page=3}}</ref> for a worldwide rental of $28 million.\n\nThe film was re-released to theaters in the United States on December 19, 1980 where it grossed an additional $18 million and again on April 10, 1987 where it grossed $17 million.<ref>{{cite web|last=Seigel|first=Robert|url=http://www.blu-ray.com/news/?id=9352|title=The Making of Walt Disney's The Aristocats|website=blu-ray.com|date=August 25, 2012|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> The film grossed $32 million worldwide from an international re-release in 1994.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Daily Variety]]|page=17|date=April 19, 1995|last=Groves|first=Don|title=O'seas Mines Big B.O.}}</ref> ''The Aristocats'' has had a lifetime gross of $55.7 million in the United States and Canada,<ref name=numbers>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-numbers.com/movies/1970/0ARIS.php|publisher=The Numbers|title=The Aristocats, Box Office Information|accessdate=January 10, 2012}}</ref> and its total lifetime worldwide box office gross is $191 million.<ref name=\"DisneyWW\"/>\n\n===Critical reaction===\n[[Howard Thompson (film critic)|Howard Thompson]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised the film as \"grand fun all the way, nicely flavored with tunes, and topped with one of the funniest jam sessions ever by a bunch of scraggly Bohemians headed by one Scat Cat.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Thompson|first=Howard|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/12/26/archives/the-aristocats-warm-animated-cartoon-by-disney-opens.html|title='The Aristocats,' Warm Animated cartoon by Disney, Opens|newspaper=The New York Times|date=December 26, 1970|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]], writing for the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'', awarded the film three stars out of four summarizing ''The Aristocats'' as \"light and pleasant and funny, the characterization is strong, and the voices of Phil Harris (O'Malley the Alley Cat) and Eva Gabor (Duchess, the mother cat) are charming in their absolute rightness.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Ebert|first=Roger|authorlink=Roger Ebert|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-aristocats-1971|title=The Aristocats Movie Review|work=rogerebert.com|date=January 1, 1971|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> [[Charles Champlin]] of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote that the film \"has a gentle good-natured charm which will delight the small-fry and their elders alike.\" He praised the animation, but remarked that the film \"lacks a certain kind of vigor, boldness and dash, a kind of a hard-focused emphasis which you would say was a Disney trademark.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Champlin|first=Charles|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/384821255/|title=Cats Star in Disney Cartoon|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|page=Section II, pgs. 4, 11|url-access=subscription|via=Newspapers.com|date=December 24, 1970|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised the film writing the film is \"[h]elped immeasurably by the voices of Phil Harris, Eva Gabor, Sterling Holloway, Scatman Crothers and others, plus some outstanding animation, songs, sentiment, some excellent dialog and even a touch of psychedelia.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/1969/film/reviews/the-aristocats-1200422129/|title=Movie Review: The Aristocats|work=Variety|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref> [[Stefan Kanfer]], reviewing for ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', noted that \"The melodies in Disney's earlier efforts have been richer. But for integration of music, comedy and plot, ''The Aristocats'' has no rivals.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Kanter|first=Stefan|title=Cinema: Top Bubble|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221210827/https://time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,904670,00.html|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,904670,00.html|magazine=Time|volume=97|issue=4|archivedate=December 21, 2008|date=January 25, 1971|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref> \n\nFor its 1987 re-release, animation historian Charles Solomon expressed criticism for its episodic plot, anachronisms, and borrowed plot elements from earlier Disney animated features, but nevertheless wrote \"[b]ut even at their least original, the Disney artists provide better animation--and more entertainment--than the recent animated features hawking ''[[The Care Bears Movie|The Care Bears]]'', ''[[Rainbow Brite and the Star Stealer|Rainbow Brite]]'' and ''[[The Transformers: The Movie|Transformers]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Solomon|first=Charles|title=Movie Review: 'The Aristocats': Walt Left A Gap|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-04-09/entertainment/ca-176_1_walt-disney|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=April 9, 1987|accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref> Writing in his book ''The Disney Films'', Disney historian and film critic [[Leonard Maltin]] wrote that \"[t]he worst that one could say of ''The AristoCats'' is that it is unmemorable. It's smoothly executed, of course, and enjoyable, but neither its superficial story nor its characters have any resonance.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Maltin|first=Leonard|authorlink=Leonard Maltin|title=The Disney Films|publisher=Disney Editions|page=262|isbn=978-0786885275|date=August 28, 2000}}</ref> Additionally, in his book ''Of Mice and Magic'', Maltin criticized the film for re-using Phil Harris to replicate ''The Jungle Book''{{'}}s Baloo, dismissing the character Thomas O'Malley as \"essentially the same character, dictated by the same voice personality.\"<ref>{{cite book|last=Maltin|first=Leonard|title=Of Mice and Magic: A History of American Animated Cartoons, Revised and Updated Edition|publisher=[[Plume (publisher)|Plume]]|isbn=978-0452259935|date=December 1, 1987|page=76}}</ref> \n\nThe [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported that the film received a 66% approval rating with an average rating of 5.9/10 based on 32 reviews. Its consensus states \"Though ''The Aristocats'' is a mostly middling effort for Disney, it is redeemed by terrific work from its voice cast and some jazzy tunes.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/aristocats|title=The Aristocats|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|work=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=September 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nThe film is recognized by [[American Film Institute]] in these lists:\n* 2008: [[AFI's 10 Top 10]]:\n** Nominated Animation Film<ref>{{cite web|url=http://connect.afi.com/site/DocServer/10top10.pdf?docID=381&AddInterest=1781 |title=AFI's 10 Top 10 Nominees |format=PDF |accessdate=2016-08-19 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716071937/http://connect.afi.com/site/DocServer/10top10.pdf?docID=381&AddInterest=1781 |archivedate=2011-07-16 }}</ref>\n\n==Canceled sequel==\nIn 2005, [[DisneyToon Studios]] originally planned to make a follow-up to the film, along with sequels to ''[[Chicken Little (2005 film)|Chicken Little]]'' (2005) and ''[[Meet the Robinsons]]'' (2007).<ref name=\"sequel\">{{cite web|url=http://jimhillmedia.com/editor_in_chief1/b/jim_hill/archive/2007/06/21/say-so-long-to-direct-to-video-sequels-disneytoon-studios-tunes-out-sharon-morrill.aspx|title=Say \"So Long !\" to direct-to-video sequels : DisneyToon Studios tunes out Sharon Morrill|last=Hill|first=Jim|publisher=Jim Hill Media|date=June 20, 2007|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Originally intended to be a 2D animated feature, Disney executives decided to produce the film in [[computer animation]] in order to garner more interest.<ref>{{cite web|last=Noyer|first=J\u00e9r\u00e9mie|url=http://animatedviews.com/2008/disneytoon-studios-and-the-sequels-that-never-were-with-tod-carter/|title=DisneyToon Studios and The Sequels That Never Were, with Tod Carter|publisher=Animated Views|date=October 20, 2008|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Additionally, the story was meant to center around Marie, Duchess's daughter, who becomes smitten by another kitten aboard a luxury cruise ship. However, she and her family must soon take on a jewel thief on the open seas.<ref>{{cite news|last=Armstrong|first=Josh|url=http://animatedviews.com/2013/from-snow-queen-to-pinocchio-ii-robert-reeces-animated-adventures-in-screenwriting/|title=From ''Snow Queen'' to ''Pinocchio II'': Robert Reece's animated adventures in screenwriting|publisher=Animated Views|date=April 22, 2013|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref> The project was canceled when [[John Lasseter]] was named Disney's new chief creative officer, in which he called off all future sequels DisneyToon had planned and instead make original productions or spin-offs.<ref name=\"sequel\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of highest-grossing animated films]]\n* [[List of highest-grossing films in France]]\n* [[List of American films of 1970]]\n* [[List of animated feature films of 1970]]\n* [[List of Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n* [[List of Disney theatrical animated features]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book|last=Koenig|first=David|title=Mouse Under Glass: Secrets of Disney Animation & Theme Parks|location=[[Irvine, California]]|publisher=Bonaventure Press|isbn=978-0964060517|year=1997|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|0065421}}\n* {{tcmdb title|67588|The Aristocats}}\n* {{bcdb title|3}}\n* [http://www.toonopedia.com/arstocat.htm ''The Aristocats''] at [[Don Markstein's Toonopedia]]. [https://www.webcitation.org/66gYYN0Ss?url=http://www.toonopedia.com/arstocat.htm Archived] from the original on April 4, 2012.\n\n{{Sherman Brothers}}\n{{Wolfgang Reitherman}}\n{{Disney theatrical animated features}}\n{{Walt Disney Animation Studios}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aristocats, The}}\n[[Category:1970 animated films]]\n[[Category:1970 films]]\n[[Category:1970s American animated films]]\n[[Category:1970s musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:1970s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure films]]\n[[Category:American musical comedy films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American romantic musical films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about cats]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]