{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Wales", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Wales}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Wales\n| image           = Empty shelves in Bangor, Wales.jpg\n| image_size      =\n| image_upright   =\n| alt             =\n| caption         = Empty shelves in [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]]\n| map1 =\n| places =\n| legend1 =\n| map2 =\n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Wales]]\n| first_case = \n| arrival_date = 28 February 2020 \n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 4,089<ref name=PublicHealthWales>{{Cite news|url=https://covid19-phwstatement.nhs.wales/|title=Public Health Wales statement on Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak|date=8 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>{{#tag:ref |Includes 29 Welsh residents currently outside Wales|group=note}}\n| suspected_cases =\n| recovery_cases =\n| deaths = 286<ref name=PublicHealthWales></ref>\n| total_ili =\n| website = [https://phw.nhs.wales/topics/latest-information-on-novel-coronavirus-covid-19/ Coronavirus in Wales]\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to Wales on 28 February 2020, with a case being reported in the [[Swansea]] area from a person who had recently returned from [[Italy]].<ref name=First>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51673068|title=First case confirmed in Wales|date=28 February 2020|work=BBC|access-date=28 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228153606/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51673068|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of 9 April the number of confirmed cases has risen to 4,089, with [[Public Health Wales]] noting that the true number of cases is likely to be higher.<ref name=\"PublicHealthWales\" />\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{align|right|{{Template:2019-20 coronavirus pandemic data/Wales medical cases chart}}}}\n=== Inital outbreak (28 February - 11 March)===\nThe first case of COVID-19 in Wales was confirmed on 28 February 2020 in a person who had returned from [[Northern Italy]], and then transferred to a specialist NHS infection centre at the [[Royal Free Hospital]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://phw.nhs.wales/news/public-health-wales-statement-on-novel-coronavirus-outbreak-in-china/|title=Public Health Wales statement on Novel coronavirus pandemic in China \u2013 Public Health Wales|last=Shankar|first=Giri|date=|website=phw.nhs.wales|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304175055/https://phw.nhs.wales/news/public-health-wales-statement-on-novel-coronavirus-outbreak-in-china/|archive-date=4 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://phw.nhs.wales/topics/latest-information-on-novel-coronavirus-covid-19/|title=Latest information on Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) \u2013 Public Health Wales|last=|first=|date=|website=phw.nhs.wales|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229190227/https://phw.nhs.wales/topics/latest-information-on-novel-coronavirus-covid-19/|archive-date=29 February 2020|access-date=5 March 2020}}</ref> The Chief Medical Officer for Wales, Dr [[Frank Atherton]], said that he was attempting to reduce the risk of transmission by taking \"all appropriate measures\".<ref name=First></ref>\n\nOn 10 March nine more cases were discovered in Wales bringing the total to 15, the first significant jump in cases.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Nine new cases in Wales brings total to 15 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51827012 |work=BBC News |date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Pandemic confirmed (11 March - 23 March) ===\nOn 11 March, the [[World Health Organisation]] declared the outbreak a [[pandemic]].<ref name=\"WHOpandemic\">{{cite web |title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 \u2013 11&nbsp;March 2020 |url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311212521/https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020 |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the first death in Wales was reported in Wrexham.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51909109 |title=Coronavirus in Wales: First Covid-19 death confirmed |work=BBC News |date=16 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316140423/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51909109 |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the [[Welsh Government]] announced that all schools in Wales would be closing by 20 March. With a limited number of schools remaining open to provide support for key workers and children with additional needs.<ref name =SchoolsClose>{{cite news |title=All schools in Wales to close by Friday |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51947148 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318132314/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51947148 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was further announced in the following days that all exams, including GCSEs and A-Levels, would be cancelled, with grades being based on existing work and predicted grades.<ref name=\"Coronavirus: How Wales' approach differs from England\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: How Wales' approach differs from England |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52094944 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Lockdown (23 March - ) ===\nOn 23 March, UK Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] announced a lockdown of the United Kingdom, with only essential services remaining open. This announcement was followed by the [[First Minister of Wales|Welsh First Minister]] [[Mark Drakeford]] announcing that the measures will also cover Wales and will come into affect from that evening.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-wales-51994269|title=Coronavirus in Wales: What happened on 23 March|work=BBC|date=23 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> The measures put in place restrict people from leaving their home for non-essential travel, with outside exercise limited to once a day. The measures that control exercise outside the home differ from those in England, where the measures in place do not stipulate that there is a once-a-day restriction, whereas the Welsh version specifically limit exercise outside the home to once a day, with the maximum fine being \u00a3120, compared to \u00a3960 in England.<ref name=\"Coronavirus: How Wales' approach differs from England\" /> <ref name=\"Coronavirus: How Wales' approach differs from England\" /> Gatherings of two or more people, except individuals in the same household, were banned, whilst pubs, restaurants (with exception for take-aways) and shops selling 'non-essential goods' were ordered to closed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52014472|title=Coronavirus: UK brings in strict curbs on life to fight virus|work=BBC News|date=24 March 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the 25 March the [[Coronavirus Act 2020]] was given Royal Assent, after passing through both Houses in the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]. The following day the [http://www.legislation.gov.uk/wsi/2020/308/contents/made Health Protection (Coronavirus, Restrictions) (Wales) Regulations 2020] was approved by the [[Welsh Assembly]], after also being approved by the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom]], giving the [[Welsh Government]] emergency powers to deal with various aspects of managing the pandemic. These new powers include the authority to: \n* Take people into or keep them in quarantine \n* Restrict or prohibit mass gatherings \n* Close premises<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-51962219|title=Coronavirus: Welsh ministers to be given 'draconian' powers|work=BBC News|date=19 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52006789|title=Coronavirus: Emergency law approved by slimmed-down Welsh Assembly|work=BBC News|date=24 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, [[Snowdon]] and other Welsh mountains were closed to the public, after a larger number of people gathered on the mountains in the preceding days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-03-26/busiest-mountain-sites-in-snowdonia-closed/|title=Busiest mountain sites in Snowdonia closed amid coronavirus lockdown|work=ITV News|date=26 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> [[Natural Resources Wales]] later announced that all sites and paths liable to have large amounts of people visiting, or pose a high risk, would be closed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://naturalresources.wales/about-us/news-and-events/statements/our-response-to-the-coronavirus-pandemic/?lang=en|title=Our response to the coronavirus pandemic|work=Natural Resources Wales|date=8 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 2 April, it was announced that the number of confirmed cases had risen above 2,000 and the number deaths in Wales had risen above 100.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://covid19-phwstatement.nhs.wales/|title=Public Health Wales statement on Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak|work=Public Health Wales|date=2 April 2020|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 5 April the number of cases rose above 3,000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-wales-52167498?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e89d3fd9cc871066e85979b%2612%20more%20deaths%20announced%262020-04-05T12%3A50%3A39.448Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:d09eaf1d-a4a1-46ba-8c00-8f245cab7555&pinned_post_asset_id=5e89d3fd9cc871066e85979b&pinned_post_type=share\n|title=12 more deaths announced|work=BBC News|date=5 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, Jitendra Rathod, a heart surgeon at [[University Hospital of Wales]], died after testing positive for coronavirus. He was thought to have been the first health worker in Wales to die after being diagnosed with the disease.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/07/senior-heart-surgeon-at-cardiff-hospital-dies-from-coronavirus|title=Senior heart surgeon at Cardiff hospital dies from coronavirus|work=The Guardian|last=Morris|first=Steven|date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April the number of deaths rose above 200.<ref name=\"PublicHealthWales\" /> On the same day, distancing measures in the workplace, enforcing a two-metre distance between people, became law in Wales, requiring employers to take \"all reasonable measures\" to comply.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52182486|title=Coronavirus: Welsh workplace two-metre rule 'not absolute ban'|work=BBC|date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April the number of cases rose above 4,000 to 4,073, with 245 deaths notified.<ref name=\"PublicHealthWales\" /> on the same day it was announced that the lockdown would not be lifted within the next week.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52215421|title=Coronavirus: Lockdown in Wales to be extended next week|work=BBC|date=8 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Healthcare response ==\n=== Hospital capacity ===\nIn 2018-19 there were around 10,563 beds available in hospitals within Wales.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://statswales.gov.wales/Catalogue/Health-and-Social-Care/NHS-Hospital-Activity/NHS-Beds/nhsbeds-by-organisation-site|title=NHS beds by organisation and site|work=Welsh Government|date=8 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> As of 7 April 2020 Wales has 369 critical care beds and there are plans in place to increase capacity further.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52204948|title=Coronavirus beds 'like pressure of 15 winters' in Wales|work=BBC|date=7 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> There are 415 ventilators currently in Welsh hospitals, with a further 1,035 ordered.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-04-05/more-than-1-000-ventilators-and-7-000-extra-hospital-beds-to-meet-expected-demand/|title=More than 1,000 ventilators and 7,000 extra hospital beds to meet expected demand|work=ITV News|date=5 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Field hospitals ===\nOn 27 March, it was announced that the [[Millennium Stadium|Principality Stadium]] in [[Cardiff]] was to be used as a field hospital for up to 2,000 beds.<ref name = MillenniumStadium>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/52024970|title=Coronavirus: Principality Stadium to be used as 2000-bed hospital|work=BBC Sport|date=27 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Each health board in Wales later announced that they are increasing the number of beds available in their current hospitals and, with the exception of [[Powys Teaching Health Board]], would be opening a number of field hospitals in available spaces.<ref name=FireldHospitals>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52091249|title=Coronavirus: Where are the extra hospital beds in Wales going?|work=BBC News|date=5 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 9 April it was announced that the field hospital to be located in the Principality Stadium would be called [[Dragon's Heart Hospital]]. On completion will be the largest hospital in Wales and the second largest hospital in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52228321|title=Coronavirus: Principality Stadium hospital taking shape|work=BBC News|date=9 April 2020|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n'''Location of field hospitals'''<ref name=\"FireldHospitals\"></ref>\n!Local health board\n! Location\n! Number of beds\n|-\n|[[Aneurin Bevan University Health Board|Aneurin Bevan]]\n|[[Grange University Hospital]], Cwmbran\n| 350\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board|Betsi Cadwaladr]]\n|[[Venue Cymru]], Llandudno\n| 350\n|-\n| [[Bangor University]]\n| 250\n|-\n| [[Deeside Leisure Centre]], Flintshire\n| 250\n|-\n|[[Cardiff and Vale University Health Board|Cardiff and Vale]]\n|[[Principality Stadium]], Cardiff\n| 2,000\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Cwm Taf Morgannwg University Health Board|Cwm Taf Morgannwg]]\n|[[The Vale Resort]], Vale of Glamorgan\n| 290\n|-\n| [[Rhondda Cynon Taf County Borough Council | Rhondda Cynon Taf council's]] Ty Trevithick offices\n| 150\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Hywel Dda University Health Board|Hywel Dda]]\n|[[Parc y Scarlets]], Llanelli\n| 350\n|-\n| [[Bluestone, Pembrokeshire| Bluestone National Park Resort]], Pembrokeshire\n| 144\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Swansea Bay University Health Board|Swansea Bay]]\n|[[Llandarcy Academy of Sport]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1,340\n|-\n| [[Bay Studios]]\n|}\n\n=== Armed forces ===\nThe [[British Army]] in Wales is currently training 60 soldiers to support the [[Welsh Ambulance Service]]. These will be used as drivers will assist in responding to emergencies and assisting with non-clinical activities. Aside from this, members of all three armed forces have been tasked with driving oxygen tankers at the Air Products facility in [[Port Talbot]]. The Army will also play a key role in the setup and running of the field hospitals set up across Wales.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/welsh-secretary-praises-uks-armed-forces-support-in-wales-fight-against-coronavirus|title=Welsh Secretary praises UK's Armed Forces' support in Wales' fight against coronavirus|work=Ministry of Defence|date=8 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Impact == \n=== Airports ===\nThe Welsh Government also announced that it would provide financial assistance to state-owned [[Cardiff Airport]], to maintain solvency during reduced operations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gov.wales/welsh-government-steps-short-term-funding-support-cardiff-airport-and-calls-change-approach|title=Welsh Government steps in with short-term funding support for Cardiff Airport and calls for change of approach from Westminster|work=Welsh Government|date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== \"At risk\" population ===\nLetters were sent to over 70,000 people who were deemed to be the 'most vulnerable', advising them to stay indoors for 12 to 16 weeks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51995997|title=Coronavirus: 70,000 people in Wales told 'stay indoors'|work=BBC|date=22 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> The Welsh Government began sending food boxes to the most in need, in order to help them stay in their homes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-04-03/first-food-boxes-delivered-to-people-shielding-from-coronavirus/|title=First food boxes delivered to people shielding from coronavirus|work=ITV News|date=3 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> The Welsh Government began sending food boxes to the most in need, in order to help them stay in their homes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52182478|title=Coronavirus: Key workers to get free childcare in Wales|work=BBC|date=6 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Businesses === \nOn 30 March, a \u00a31.1 billion support package for businesses and public services affected by the pandemic, included a \u00a3500 million ''economy crisis fund'', \u00a3100 million in loans, and \u00a3400 million in emergency funding.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52085642|title=Coronavirus: Welsh Government announces \u00a31.1bn funding|work=BBC News|date=30 March 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nOn 15 March [[Bangor University]] cancelled all lectures with immediate effect, with teaching resuming online on 23 March. [[Cardiff University]] and [[Swansea University]] both also announce that they would be moving towards remote learning and online lectures from the 23 March.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51896536|title=Coronavirus in Wales: Schools may close, warns Vaughan Gething|work=BBC|date=15 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the [[Welsh Government]] announced that all schools and nurseries in Wales would be closing by 20 March, initially for a period of four weeks, although Education Minister [[Kirsty Williams]] said that it would very likely for a \"considerable period of time\". A limited number of schools are remaining open to provide support for key workers and children with additional needs.<ref name=\"SchoolsClose\" /> It was further announced in the following days that all exams, including GCSEs and A-Levels, would be cancelled, with grades being based on existing work and predicted grades.<ref name=\"Coronavirus: How Wales' approach differs from England\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: How Wales' approach differs from England |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52094944 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April the Welsh Assembly announced funding for free child care for all children of key workers under five years old.<ref>>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Key workers to get free childcare in Wales|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52182478 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Health ===\nOn 1 April, it was announced that during the pandemic home abortions would be allowed for women in the first nine weeks of pregnancy, following an online or telephone consultation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52118335|title=Coronavirus: Home abortions allowed in Wales during pandemic|work=BBC News|date=1 April 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nVirtual GP appointments were also rolled out across Wales, sooner than originally anticipated, allowing for phone consultations, with video consultations also available if needed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gov.wales/virtual-doctor-appointments-rolled-out-across-wales|title=Virtual doctor appointments rolled out across Wales|work=Welsh Government|date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Politics ===\nPlans by the Welsh Government to extend the right to vote to prisoners serving less that were shelved, with ministers unable to commit \"any official resource\" the changes due to the pandemic. Plans to extend the vote and enfranchise sixteen and seventeen year olds were to continue ahead however.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52221041|title=Coronavirus: Prisoner votes in Welsh local elections plan shelved|work=BBC|date=9 April 2020|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n=== Prisions ===\nOn 19 March, it was revealed that around 75 officers at [[HMP Berwyn]] in [[Wrexham County Borough]] were off work due to sickness or self-isolation, and 22 prisoners showing symptoms of coronavirus were being isolated by the prison. However, the prison had enough staff members to remain fully operational.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rees |first1=Jenny |title=Seventy-five prison officers off sick or isolating |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51966387 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320154011/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51966387 |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, three inmates at [[HMP Swansea]] had been confirmed as testing positive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-wales-52091590?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e839f5aa8854e067111aa04%26Three%20Swansea%20prisoners%20test%20positive%262020-03-31T21%3A04%3A55.522Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:077f9811-446c-452b-9773-f0a001e984af&pinned_post_asset_id=5e839f5aa8854e067111aa04&pinned_post_type=share|title=Three Swansea prisoners test positive|work=BBC News|date=31 March 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April it was announced that some low risk prisoners, with two months or less still to serve, would be released on temporary licence. Those released will be electronically tagged. No inmates convicted of COVID-19 offences would be considered for release.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52165919|title=Coronavirus: Low-risk prisoners set for early release|work=BBC News|date=4 April 2020|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Religious services ===\nThe [[Church in Wales]] announced the suspension of its public gatherings, including church services, along with the postponement of weddings and baptisms. The Muslim Council of Britain and the Roman Catholic church announced similar moves, with many religious services being streamed online.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51974782|title=Coronavirus: Church and religious services off across Wales|work=BBC|date=22 March 2020|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-03-19/catholic-church-suspends-public-worship-to-slow-spread-of-coronavirus|title=Catholic Church suspends public worship to slow spread of coronavirus|work=ITV News|date=19 March 2020|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Sports ===\nOn 13 March, the [[Six Nations Championship|Six Nations]] Wales vs Scotland fixture was postponed for a year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51853907|title=Six Nations: Wales v Scotland off because of coronavirus|date=13 March 2020|work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313141835/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51853907|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Welsh Rugby Union]] also suspended all forms of rugby in Wales from 14 to 30 March, which also extended to the end of the season of 20 March.\n\n=== Supermarkets ===\n[[File:Rationing notice, Sainsbury's north London.jpg|thumb|Some supermarkets began to limit purchases of items in high demand. 12 March.]]\nIn March 2020, supermarkets announced restrictions on the number of items people could buy, with each company setting their own limits. This was seen as a reaction to a large number of members of the public stockpiling food.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/18/asda-puts-restrictions-on-shoppers-to-limit-stockpiling-coronavirus|title=UK supermarkets impose tight new rules to prevent hoarding|work=The Guardian|date=18 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> Stores began implementing social distancing regulations, with many stores attaching tape to the floor to separate people by two metres and limiting the number of people in the store at a time. Many stores installed protective screens on checkouts to help protect workers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52022240|title=Coronavirus: Supermarkets limit shoppers as rules tighten|work=BBC|date=24 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics == \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n'''Situation on 8 April 2020'''<ref name=\"PublicHealthWales\"></ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://public.tableau.com/profile/public.health.wales.health.protection#!/vizhome/RapidCOVID-19virology-Public/Headlinesummary|title=Cases and tests, by Local Authority of residence|work=Public Health Wales|date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n! Health board\n! Local authority\n! Cases\n! Total cases\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | [[Aneurin Bevan University Health Board|Aneurin Bevan]]\n| [[Blaenau Gwent]]\n| 130\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 1,211\n|-\n| [[Caerphilly]]\n| 313\n|-\n| [[Monmouthshire]]\n| 135\n|-\n| [[Newport, Wales|Newport]]\n| 447\n|-\n| [[Torfaen]]\n| 186\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" | [[Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board|Betsi Cadwaladr]]\n| Anglesey\n| 16\n| rowspan=\"6\" | 277\n|-\n| [[Conwy]]\n| 33\n|-\n| [[Denbighshire]]\n| 56\n|-\n| [[Flintshire]]\n| 75\n|-\n| [[Gwynedd]]\n| 34\n|-\n| [[Wrexham]]\n| 63\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Cardiff and Vale University Health Board|Cardiff and Vale]]\n| [[Cardiff]]\n| 777\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1,013\n|-\n| [[Vale of Glamorgan]]\n| 236\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Cwm Taf Morgannwg University Health Board|Cwm Taf Morgannwg]]\n| [[Bridgend]]\n| 145\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 618\n|-\n| [[Merthyr Tydfil]]\n| 80\n|-\n| [[Rhondda Cynon Taf]]\n| 393\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Hywel Dda University Health Board|Hywel Dda]]\n| [[Carmarthenshire]]\n| 190\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 283\n|-\n| [[Ceredigion]]\n| 24\n|-\n| [[Pembrokeshire]]\n| 69\n|-\n| [[Powys Teaching Health Board|Powys]]\n| [[Powys]]\n| 62\n| 62\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Swansea Bay University Health Board|Swansea Bay]]\n| [[Neath Port Talbot]]\n| 175\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 534\n|-\n| [[Swansea]]\n| 359\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | Location Unknown\n| 46\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | Welsh resident outside Wales\n| 29\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | Wales Total\n| 4,044\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | '''Total'''\n| '''4,073'''\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in England]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Northern Ireland]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Scotland]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|Wales]]\n[[Category:2020 in Wales]]\n[[Category:Health in Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Wales}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Wales\n| image           = Empty shelves in Bangor, Wales.jpg\n| image_size      =\n| image_upright   =\n| alt             =\n| caption         = Empty shelves in [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]]\n| map1 =\n| places =\n| legend1 =\n| map2 =\n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Wales]]\n| first_case = \n| arrival_date = 28 February 2020 \n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = 4,089<ref name=PublicHealthWales>{{Cite news|url=https://covid19-phwstatement.nhs.wales/|title=Public Health Wales statement on Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak|date=8 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>{{#tag:ref |Includes 29 Welsh residents currently outside Wales|group=note}}\n| suspected_cases =\n| recovery_cases =\n| deaths = 286<ref name=PublicHealthWales></ref>\n| total_ili =\n| website = [https://phw.nhs.wales/topics/latest-information-on-novel-coronavirus-covid-19/ Coronavirus in Wales]\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to Wales on 28 February 2020, with a case being reported in the [[Swansea]] area from a person who had recently returned from [[Italy]].<ref name=First>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51673068|title=First case confirmed in Wales|date=28 February 2020|work=BBC|access-date=28 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228153606/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-51673068|archive-date=28 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As of 9 April the number of confirmed cases has risen to 4,089, with [[Public Health Wales]] noting that the true number of cases is likely to be higher.<ref name=\"PublicHealthWales\" />\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{align|right|{{Template:2019-20 coronavirus pandemic data/Wales medical cases chart}}}}\n=== Inital outbreak (28 February - 11 March)===\nThe first case of COVID-19 in Wales was confirmed on 28 February 2020 in a person who had returned from [[Northern Italy]], and then transferred to a specialist NHS infection centre at the [[Royal Free Hospital]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://phw.nhs.wales/news/public-health-wales-statement-on-novel-coronavirus-outbreak-in-china/|title=Public Health Wales statement on Novel coronavirus pandemic in China \u2013 Public Health Wales|last=Shankar|first=Giri|date=|website=phw.nhs.wales|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304175055/https://phw.nhs.wales/news/public-health-wales-statement-on-novel-coronavirus-outbreak-in-china/|archive-date=4 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://phw.nhs.wales/topics/latest-information-on-novel-coronavirus-covid-19/|title=Latest information on Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) \u2013 Public Health Wales|last=|first=|date=|website=phw.nhs.wales|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229190227/https://phw.nhs.wales/topics/latest-information-on-novel-coronavirus-covid-19/|archive-date=29 February 2020|access-date=5 March 2020}}</ref> The Chief Medical Officer for Wales, Dr [[Frank Atherton]], said that he was attempting to reduce the risk of transmission by taking \"all appropriate measures\".<ref name=First></ref>\n\nOn 10 March nine more cases were discovered in Wales bringing the total to 15, the first significant jump in cases.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Nine new cases in Wales brings total to 15 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51827012 |work=BBC News |date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Pandemic confirmed (11 March - 23 March) ===\nOn 11 March, the [[World Health Organisation]] declared the outbreak a [[pandemic]].<ref name=\"WHOpandemic\">{{cite web |title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on COVID-19 \u2013 11&nbsp;March 2020 |url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311212521/https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-covid-19---11-march-2020 |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 16 March, the first death in Wales was reported in Wrexham.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51909109 |title=Coronavirus in Wales: First Covid-19 death confirmed |work=BBC News |date=16 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316140423/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51909109 |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the [[Welsh Government]] announced that all schools in Wales would be closing by 20 March. With a limited number of schools remaining open to provide support for key workers and children with additional needs.<ref name =SchoolsClose>{{cite news |title=All schools in Wales to close by Friday |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51947148 |accessdate=18 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318132314/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51947148 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> It was further announced in the following days that all exams, including GCSEs and A-Levels, would be cancelled, with grades being based on existing work and predicted grades.<ref name=\"Coronavirus: How Wales' approach differs from England\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: How Wales' approach differs from England |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52094944 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Lockdown (23 March - ) ===\nOn 23 March, UK Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]] announced a lockdown of the United Kingdom, with only essential services remaining open. This announcement was followed by the [[First Minister of Wales|Welsh First Minister]] [[Mark Drakeford]] announcing that the measures will also cover Wales and will come into affect from that evening.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-wales-51994269|title=Coronavirus in Wales: What happened on 23 March|work=BBC|date=23 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> The measures put in place restrict people from leaving their home for non-essential travel, with outside exercise limited to once a day. The measures that control exercise outside the home differ from those in England, where the measures in place do not stipulate that there is a once-a-day restriction, whereas the Welsh version specifically limit exercise outside the home to once a day, with the maximum fine being \u00a3120, compared to \u00a3960 in England.<ref name=\"Coronavirus: How Wales' approach differs from England\" /> <ref name=\"Coronavirus: How Wales' approach differs from England\" /> Gatherings of two or more people, except individuals in the same household, were banned, whilst pubs, restaurants (with exception for take-aways) and shops selling 'non-essential goods' were ordered to closed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52014472|title=Coronavirus: UK brings in strict curbs on life to fight virus|work=BBC News|date=24 March 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn the 25 March the [[Coronavirus Act 2020]] was given Royal Assent, after passing through both Houses in the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]. The following day the [http://www.legislation.gov.uk/wsi/2020/308/contents/made Health Protection (Coronavirus, Restrictions) (Wales) Regulations 2020] was approved by the [[Welsh Assembly]], after also being approved by the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom]], giving the [[Welsh Government]] emergency powers to deal with various aspects of managing the pandemic. These new powers include the authority to: \n* Take people into or keep them in quarantine \n* Restrict or prohibit mass gatherings \n* Close premises<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-51962219|title=Coronavirus: Welsh ministers to be given 'draconian' powers|work=BBC News|date=19 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52006789|title=Coronavirus: Emergency law approved by slimmed-down Welsh Assembly|work=BBC News|date=24 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March, [[Snowdon]] and other Welsh mountains were closed to the public, after a larger number of people gathered on the mountains in the preceding days.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-03-26/busiest-mountain-sites-in-snowdonia-closed/|title=Busiest mountain sites in Snowdonia closed amid coronavirus lockdown|work=ITV News|date=26 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> [[Natural Resources Wales]] later announced that all sites and paths liable to have large amounts of people visiting, or pose a high risk, would be closed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://naturalresources.wales/about-us/news-and-events/statements/our-response-to-the-coronavirus-pandemic/?lang=en|title=Our response to the coronavirus pandemic|work=Natural Resources Wales|date=8 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 2 April, it was announced that the number of confirmed cases had risen above 2,000 and the number deaths in Wales had risen above 100.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://covid19-phwstatement.nhs.wales/|title=Public Health Wales statement on Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) outbreak|work=Public Health Wales|date=2 April 2020|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 5 April the number of cases rose above 3,000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-wales-52167498?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e89d3fd9cc871066e85979b%2612%20more%20deaths%20announced%262020-04-05T12%3A50%3A39.448Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:d09eaf1d-a4a1-46ba-8c00-8f245cab7555&pinned_post_asset_id=5e89d3fd9cc871066e85979b&pinned_post_type=share\n|title=12 more deaths announced|work=BBC News|date=5 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April, Jitendra Rathod, a heart surgeon at [[University Hospital of Wales]], died after testing positive for coronavirus. He was thought to have been the first health worker in Wales to die after being diagnosed with the disease.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/07/senior-heart-surgeon-at-cardiff-hospital-dies-from-coronavirus|title=Senior heart surgeon at Cardiff hospital dies from coronavirus|work=The Guardian|last=Morris|first=Steven|date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 April the number of deaths rose above 200.<ref name=\"PublicHealthWales\" /> On the same day, distancing measures in the workplace, enforcing a two-metre distance between people, became law in Wales, requiring employers to take \"all reasonable measures\" to comply.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52182486|title=Coronavirus: Welsh workplace two-metre rule 'not absolute ban'|work=BBC|date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 April the number of cases rose above 4,000 to 4,073, with 245 deaths notified.<ref name=\"PublicHealthWales\" /> on the same day it was announced that the lockdown would not be lifted within the next week.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52215421|title=Coronavirus: Lockdown in Wales to be extended next week|work=BBC|date=8 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Healthcare response ==\n=== Hospital capacity ===\nIn 2018-19 there were around 10,563 beds available in hospitals within Wales.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://statswales.gov.wales/Catalogue/Health-and-Social-Care/NHS-Hospital-Activity/NHS-Beds/nhsbeds-by-organisation-site|title=NHS beds by organisation and site|work=Welsh Government|date=8 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> As of 7 April 2020 Wales has 369 critical care beds and there are plans in place to increase capacity further.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52204948|title=Coronavirus beds 'like pressure of 15 winters' in Wales|work=BBC|date=7 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> There are 415 ventilators currently in Welsh hospitals, with a further 1,035 ordered.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-04-05/more-than-1-000-ventilators-and-7-000-extra-hospital-beds-to-meet-expected-demand/|title=More than 1,000 ventilators and 7,000 extra hospital beds to meet expected demand|work=ITV News|date=5 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Field hospitals ===\nOn 27 March, it was announced that the [[Millennium Stadium|Principality Stadium]] in [[Cardiff]] was to be used as a field hospital for up to 2,000 beds.<ref name = MillenniumStadium>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/52024970|title=Coronavirus: Principality Stadium to be used as 2000-bed hospital|work=BBC Sport|date=27 March 2020|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref> Each health board in Wales later announced that they are increasing the number of beds available in their current hospitals and, with the exception of [[Powys Teaching Health Board]], would be opening a number of field hospitals in available spaces.<ref name=FireldHospitals>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52091249|title=Coronavirus: Where are the extra hospital beds in Wales going?|work=BBC News|date=5 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn 9 April it was announced that the field hospital to be located in the Principality Stadium would be called [[Dragon's Heart Hospital]]. On completion will be the largest hospital in Wales and the second largest hospital in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52228321|title=Coronavirus: Principality Stadium hospital taking shape|work=BBC News|date=9 April 2020|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n'''Location of field hospitals'''<ref name=\"FireldHospitals\"></ref>\n!Local health board\n! Location\n! Number of beds\n|-\n|[[Aneurin Bevan University Health Board|Aneurin Bevan]]\n|[[Grange University Hospital]], Cwmbran\n| 350\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board|Betsi Cadwaladr]]\n|[[Venue Cymru]], Llandudno\n| 350\n|-\n| [[Bangor University]]\n| 250\n|-\n| [[Deeside Leisure Centre]], Flintshire\n| 250\n|-\n|[[Cardiff and Vale University Health Board|Cardiff and Vale]]\n|[[Principality Stadium]], Cardiff\n| 2,000\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Cwm Taf Morgannwg University Health Board|Cwm Taf Morgannwg]]\n|[[The Vale Resort]], Vale of Glamorgan\n| 290\n|-\n| [[Rhondda Cynon Taf County Borough Council | Rhondda Cynon Taf council's]] Ty Trevithick offices\n| 150\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Hywel Dda University Health Board|Hywel Dda]]\n|[[Parc y Scarlets]], Llanelli\n| 350\n|-\n| [[Bluestone, Pembrokeshire| Bluestone National Park Resort]], Pembrokeshire\n| 144\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Swansea Bay University Health Board|Swansea Bay]]\n|[[Llandarcy Academy of Sport]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1,340\n|-\n| [[Bay Studios]]\n|}\n\n=== Armed forces ===\nThe [[British Army]] in Wales is currently training 60 soldiers to support the [[Welsh Ambulance Service]]. These will be used as drivers will assist in responding to emergencies and assisting with non-clinical activities. Aside from this, members of all three armed forces have been tasked with driving oxygen tankers at the Air Products facility in [[Port Talbot]]. The Army will also play a key role in the setup and running of the field hospitals set up across Wales.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/welsh-secretary-praises-uks-armed-forces-support-in-wales-fight-against-coronavirus|title=Welsh Secretary praises UK's Armed Forces' support in Wales' fight against coronavirus|work=Ministry of Defence|date=8 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Impact == \n=== Airports ===\nThe Welsh Government also announced that it would provide financial assistance to state-owned [[Cardiff Airport]], to maintain solvency during reduced operations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gov.wales/welsh-government-steps-short-term-funding-support-cardiff-airport-and-calls-change-approach|title=Welsh Government steps in with short-term funding support for Cardiff Airport and calls for change of approach from Westminster|work=Welsh Government|date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== \"At risk\" population ===\nLetters were sent to over 70,000 people who were deemed to be the 'most vulnerable', advising them to stay indoors for 12 to 16 weeks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51995997|title=Coronavirus: 70,000 people in Wales told 'stay indoors'|work=BBC|date=22 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> The Welsh Government began sending food boxes to the most in need, in order to help them stay in their homes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-04-03/first-food-boxes-delivered-to-people-shielding-from-coronavirus/|title=First food boxes delivered to people shielding from coronavirus|work=ITV News|date=3 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> The Welsh Government began sending food boxes to the most in need, in order to help them stay in their homes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52182478|title=Coronavirus: Key workers to get free childcare in Wales|work=BBC|date=6 April 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Businesses === \nOn 30 March, a \u00a31.1 billion support package for businesses and public services affected by the pandemic, included a \u00a3500 million ''economy crisis fund'', \u00a3100 million in loans, and \u00a3400 million in emergency funding.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52085642|title=Coronavirus: Welsh Government announces \u00a31.1bn funding|work=BBC News|date=30 March 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nOn 15 March [[Bangor University]] cancelled all lectures with immediate effect, with teaching resuming online on 23 March. [[Cardiff University]] and [[Swansea University]] both also announce that they would be moving towards remote learning and online lectures from the 23 March.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51896536|title=Coronavirus in Wales: Schools may close, warns Vaughan Gething|work=BBC|date=15 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the [[Welsh Government]] announced that all schools and nurseries in Wales would be closing by 20 March, initially for a period of four weeks, although Education Minister [[Kirsty Williams]] said that it would very likely for a \"considerable period of time\". A limited number of schools are remaining open to provide support for key workers and children with additional needs.<ref name=\"SchoolsClose\" /> It was further announced in the following days that all exams, including GCSEs and A-Levels, would be cancelled, with grades being based on existing work and predicted grades.<ref name=\"Coronavirus: How Wales' approach differs from England\">{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: How Wales' approach differs from England |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52094944 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 April the Welsh Assembly announced funding for free child care for all children of key workers under five years old.<ref>>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Key workers to get free childcare in Wales|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52182478 |accessdate=6 April 2020 |agency=BBC |publisher=BBC News |date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Health ===\nOn 1 April, it was announced that during the pandemic home abortions would be allowed for women in the first nine weeks of pregnancy, following an online or telephone consultation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-52118335|title=Coronavirus: Home abortions allowed in Wales during pandemic|work=BBC News|date=1 April 2020|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> \n\nVirtual GP appointments were also rolled out across Wales, sooner than originally anticipated, allowing for phone consultations, with video consultations also available if needed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://gov.wales/virtual-doctor-appointments-rolled-out-across-wales|title=Virtual doctor appointments rolled out across Wales|work=Welsh Government|date=3 April 2020|access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Politics ===\nPlans by the Welsh Government to extend the right to vote to prisoners serving less that were shelved, with ministers unable to commit \"any official resource\" the changes due to the pandemic. Plans to extend the vote and enfranchise sixteen and seventeen year olds were to continue ahead however.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-politics-52221041|title=Coronavirus: Prisoner votes in Welsh local elections plan shelved|work=BBC|date=9 April 2020|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n=== Prisions ===\nOn 19 March, it was revealed that around 75 officers at [[HMP Berwyn]] in [[Wrexham County Borough]] were off work due to sickness or self-isolation, and 22 prisoners showing symptoms of coronavirus were being isolated by the prison. However, the prison had enough staff members to remain fully operational.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rees |first1=Jenny |title=Seventy-five prison officers off sick or isolating |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51966387 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |work=BBC News |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320154011/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51966387 |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, three inmates at [[HMP Swansea]] had been confirmed as testing positive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-wales-52091590?ns_mchannel=social&ns_source=twitter&ns_campaign=bbc_live&ns_linkname=5e839f5aa8854e067111aa04%26Three%20Swansea%20prisoners%20test%20positive%262020-03-31T21%3A04%3A55.522Z&ns_fee=0&pinned_post_locator=urn:asset:077f9811-446c-452b-9773-f0a001e984af&pinned_post_asset_id=5e839f5aa8854e067111aa04&pinned_post_type=share|title=Three Swansea prisoners test positive|work=BBC News|date=31 March 2020|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 April it was announced that some low risk prisoners, with two months or less still to serve, would be released on temporary licence. Those released will be electronically tagged. No inmates convicted of COVID-19 offences would be considered for release.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-52165919|title=Coronavirus: Low-risk prisoners set for early release|work=BBC News|date=4 April 2020|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Religious services ===\nThe [[Church in Wales]] announced the suspension of its public gatherings, including church services, along with the postponement of weddings and baptisms. The Muslim Council of Britain and the Roman Catholic church announced similar moves, with many religious services being streamed online.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-51974782|title=Coronavirus: Church and religious services off across Wales|work=BBC|date=22 March 2020|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itv.com/news/wales/2020-03-19/catholic-church-suspends-public-worship-to-slow-spread-of-coronavirus|title=Catholic Church suspends public worship to slow spread of coronavirus|work=ITV News|date=19 March 2020|access-date=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Sports ===\nOn 13 March, the [[Six Nations Championship|Six Nations]] Wales vs Scotland fixture was postponed for a year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51853907|title=Six Nations: Wales v Scotland off because of coronavirus|date=13 March 2020|work=BBC Sport|access-date=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313141835/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/51853907|archive-date=13 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Welsh Rugby Union]] also suspended all forms of rugby in Wales from 14 to 30 March, which also extended to the end of the season of 20 March.\n\n=== Supermarkets ===\n[[File:Rationing notice, Sainsbury's north London.jpg|thumb|Some supermarkets began to limit purchases of items in high demand. 12 March.]]\nIn March 2020, supermarkets announced restrictions on the number of items people could buy, with each company setting their own limits. This was seen as a reaction to a large number of members of the public stockpiling food.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2020/mar/18/asda-puts-restrictions-on-shoppers-to-limit-stockpiling-coronavirus|title=UK supermarkets impose tight new rules to prevent hoarding|work=The Guardian|date=18 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> Stores began implementing social distancing regulations, with many stores attaching tape to the floor to separate people by two metres and limiting the number of people in the store at a time. Many stores installed protective screens on checkouts to help protect workers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-52022240|title=Coronavirus: Supermarkets limit shoppers as rules tighten|work=BBC|date=24 March 2020|access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics == \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n'''Situation on 8 April 2020'''<ref name=\"PublicHealthWales\"></ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://public.tableau.com/profile/public.health.wales.health.protection#!/vizhome/RapidCOVID-19virology-Public/Headlinesummary|title=Cases and tests, by Local Authority of residence|work=Public Health Wales|date=7 April 2020|access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n! Health board\n! Local authority\n! Cases\n! Total cases\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" | [[Aneurin Bevan University Health Board|Aneurin Bevan]]\n| [[Blaenau Gwent]]\n| 130\n| rowspan=\"5\" | 1,211\n|-\n| [[Caerphilly]]\n| 313\n|-\n| [[Monmouthshire]]\n| 135\n|-\n| [[Newport, Wales|Newport]]\n| 447\n|-\n| [[Torfaen]]\n| 186\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" | [[Betsi Cadwaladr University Health Board|Betsi Cadwaladr]]\n| Anglesey\n| 16\n| rowspan=\"6\" | 277\n|-\n| [[Conwy]]\n| 33\n|-\n| [[Denbighshire]]\n| 56\n|-\n| [[Flintshire]]\n| 75\n|-\n| [[Gwynedd]]\n| 34\n|-\n| [[Wrexham]]\n| 63\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Cardiff and Vale University Health Board|Cardiff and Vale]]\n| [[Cardiff]]\n| 777\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1,013\n|-\n| [[Vale of Glamorgan]]\n| 236\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Cwm Taf Morgannwg University Health Board|Cwm Taf Morgannwg]]\n| [[Bridgend]]\n| 145\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 618\n|-\n| [[Merthyr Tydfil]]\n| 80\n|-\n| [[Rhondda Cynon Taf]]\n| 393\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Hywel Dda University Health Board|Hywel Dda]]\n| [[Carmarthenshire]]\n| 190\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 283\n|-\n| [[Ceredigion]]\n| 24\n|-\n| [[Pembrokeshire]]\n| 69\n|-\n| [[Powys Teaching Health Board|Powys]]\n| [[Powys]]\n| 62\n| 62\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Swansea Bay University Health Board|Swansea Bay]]\n| [[Neath Port Talbot]]\n| 175\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 534\n|-\n| [[Swansea]]\n| 359\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | Location Unknown\n| 46\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | Welsh resident outside Wales\n| 29\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | Wales Total\n| 4,044\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" | '''Total'''\n| '''4,073'''\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in England]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Northern Ireland]]\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Scotland]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|Wales]]\n[[Category:2020 in Wales]]\n[[Category:Health in Wales]]\n", "name_user": "Yadsalohcin", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed table", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.or